<SECOND>AM-Dental Gas Deaths,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Found Dead In Storage Room From Apparent Asphyxiation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEDAR CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two young men and two young women who apparently were inhaling laughing gas to get high were found dead Monday in a storeroom of a building housing a dental clinic, authorities said. The bodies were found shortly before noon in a small room near an empty tank of nitrous oxide, a gas used by dentists as an anesthetic, <LOCATION> Iron </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>. `` It's believed that they were inhaling the gas,'' he said. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said there was no sign of forced entry. He identified the victims as <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregerson </PERSON>, 18, and <PERSON> Shawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 19, both of <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Cherie </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, 20, of Fillmore; and <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Probert </PERSON>, 20, of Scipio. The bodies were sent to the state medical examiner's office for a determination of the cause of death, but <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said preliminary investigation shows they were asphyxiated. `` It's just a tragic accident and our hearts go out to the families,'' he said. `` We've never had injuries or deaths due to nitrous oxide. It's common throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for people to try to gain access to that to try to get high.''
