<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Border     08-08 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Border,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Territorial Disputes Jeopardize Iran-Iraq Truce Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Territorial conflicts that brought about the war between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> eight years ago will jeopardize the truce that both countries have accepted, an Iranian specialist in international law said Monday. A 1975 border treaty could be the solution and for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> there `` should be no questions,'' said <PERSON> Alireza </PERSON> <PERSON> Deyihim </PERSON>, deputy dean of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s diplomatic academy that is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. He said in an interview that both countries had accepted the 1975 pact and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> `` clearly violated international law'' when it abrogated the treaty unilaterally in 1979. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in September 1980 after a series of border skirmishes. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> agreed Monday to accept the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>'s call for a cease-fire. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution 598 also states that both <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> and Iranian forces should withdraw `` to the internationally recognized borders without delay'' after the cease-fire is in place. <PERSON> Deyihim </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> believes that phrase means the forces should withdraw to the borders agreed upon in the 1975 treaty between <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s government of <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlevi </PERSON> that was overthrown in 1979 in the revolt led by <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. `` Both countries have ratified this treaty and announced ratification to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Deyihim </PERSON> said. `` That treaty settled all problems including the border in the <LOCATION> Shatt-al-Arab </LOCATION>,'' the 120-mile waterway that flows into the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and forms the southern border between the warring neighbors. <PERSON> Deyihim </PERSON>, who entered <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s foreign service 17 years ago and was involved in the 1975 treaty negotiations, said if <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had wanted to renegotiate parts of the agreement it could have used the complaints procedure that is part of the pact. He claimed <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had removed many of about 570 markers set to delineate the 730-mile border after the 1975 treaty. `` They removed them ... and even pulled out trees'' that marked the border, he said. `` We hope that this -LRB- border issue -RRB- does not cause a delay in implementing the cease-fire.'' he added.
</TEXT>
