<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-AIDSDrug     08-08 0917</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-AIDS Drug,0942</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trickle of Americans Seek Possible Anti-AIDS Drug In Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s doors are hesitantly open to a trickle of Americans seeking an experimental anti-AIDS drug that has not been approved for use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The drug, dextran sulfate, was developed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the 1960s and has been used to treat arteriosclerosis and high cholesterol. Within the last year, however, Japanese and American researchers have shown in the test tube that the compound is a potent agent against infection by HIV, which causes the fatal acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Now researchers are trying to determine whether dextran sulfate is effective when given to AIDS patients and whether they can take large doses over a long period. The drug's potential has received wide publicity, and some American AIDS sufferers or their friends have sought the drug in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` A year ago I started receiving calls from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> guys who asked if dextran sulfate was available,'' said <PERSON> Manabu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON>, manager at the American Pharmacy in central <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` I had no idea it could be used against AIDS.'' Now, <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON> says, two or three Americans come in every month seeking dextran sulfate. The American Pharmacy is one of three pharmacies in the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> area that were authorized two months ago to sell the compound under tight control _ but without a doctor's prescription _ by the <ORGANIZATION> Phamarceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, one of about a dozen makers of dextran sulfate in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` We talked it over with the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, and decided for humanitarian reasons it would be sold to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> tourists,'' said <PERSON> Kowa </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Endo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Endo </PERSON> said the company limited over-the-counter sales to three pharmacies because if dextran sulfate were widely available, it would be difficult to give proper warnings to purchasers. `` There could be damage, and we as a pharmaceutical company are quite worried about this,'' he said. A buyer at the American Pharmacy must sign a form in English stating how many tablets were purchased, that they were for personal use, that the drug is approved in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for treatment of high cholesterol at a dosage of 450-900 milligrams a day, and that it affects blood coagulation and should not be used by hemophiliacs. A separate page includes information on adverse reactions, such as skin eruptions, anorexia and diarrhea. The dosages being considered for AIDS therapy are much higher than routine use in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` We do n't have any information on this drug in such high dosage,'' <PERSON> Endo </PERSON> said, adding that if a patient takes a high dosage, `` the risks might be higher.'' He declined to name all three pharmacies permitted to sell the drug, though he said their names were well-known to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francicso </LOCATION> AIDS sufferers. He said <PERSON> Kowa </PERSON> was concerned that people that people with irrational fears of AIDS might experiment with dangerously high doses. The three pharmacies reportedly have anywhere from two to 30 customers per month. The company also worries that buyers might start a black market business exporting the drug, which sells at the American Pharmacy for $ 272 for 1,000 300-milligram tablets. <PERSON> Kowa </PERSON> is not doing AIDS research with dextran sulfate. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s leader in that area is a 70-year-old chemical firm, <ORGANIZATION> Ueno </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION>, which has no medicines currently on the market Ueno is worried that its research, backed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, may be harmed by personal imports by American AIDS sufferers. `` From a humane point of view, we will not do anything'' to stop the drug's sale to Americans, said Dr. <PERSON> Ryuji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueno </PERSON>, director of the department of medicine at his family's company. `` We are just a little disappointed, though.'' At stake for the company is the possibility of a lucrative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market if the drug is proved effective. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> recently reaffirmed its policy of letting AIDS patients import drugs for their personal use even if they have not been approved. But the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> last week ordered inspectors to block imports of dextran sulfate from <ORGANIZATION> Polydex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, saying the Canadian company was promoting its unproven drug in violation of federal rules. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has approved clinical tests of <PERSON> Ueno </PERSON>'s dextran sulfate compound but approval for use of the drug in AIDS therapy still is a long way off, <PERSON> Ueno </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his laboratory near <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>. So far, he said, the drug has been tested for side effects on patients at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> General </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. The current phase of tests, which began July 7, involves giving patients increasingly higher doses to see whether the drug is effective against HIV and to determine its side effects, <PERSON> Ueno </PERSON> said. The research is being done at nine AIDS-treatment centers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and will take six months. <PERSON> Ueno </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> had granted his compound `` open drug status,'' meaning authorities will help fund research and give the drug a protected market for seven years if it is successful. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has had only 80 AIDS cases, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION>, so few that the drug could not be tested on patients. AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual contact. Other means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers. AIDS can also be passed from mother to child at or before birth.
</TEXT>
