<FIRST>r i AM-HaitiPriest     08-08 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti Priest,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expelled Canadian priest said he feared for his life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic priest deported from <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> after he criticized the military government, said in an interview Sunday he told his superiors last week that `` something could happen to me.'' `` I told them that if they heard I'd received a bullet in my head, do n't be surprised,'' <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON> said in the telephone interview. The priest, a native of <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION>, Ont., arrived in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> Saturday on a flight from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> He was asked why be believed he could be the target of killers and said `` the system is becoming much more repressive and anything is possible.'' <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON> said he was expelled because he spoke out against injustice and encouraged the poor to organize politically. He acknowledged he had refused a military demand to provide a list of parish members who attended one of his recent religious services. He said the troopers who seized him Friday did not have a warrant for his arrest and did not know his name. `` All they knew was that I was the -LRB- parish -RRB- priest and therefore wicked,'' he said. <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON> gave this account of his expulsion: Several soldiers entered his parish in <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Goave </LOCATION>, 30 miles southeast of the capital of <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>, and drove him to a prison where he was not allowed to call the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. The soldiers took him to the airport where he was placed aboard a commercial jetliner, and when he tried to resist they struck him with their rifles and threw him face down on the aisle. It was a New York-bound flight and after spending the night in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> he flew to <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>. A Haitian radio station said the government accused <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON> of making `` insulting public declarations which are liable to disturb the social and political order established in the country.'' A statement by the Canadian government said it was `` deeply distressed and unhappy at the cavalier way that Father <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON> was deported and -LRB- we -RRB- will be expressing our dissatisfaction to the Haitian authorities.'' <PERSON> Poirier </PERSON> was seized the same day that <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s leader, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>, was touring the Grand Goave region. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> said at that time that <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s problems should be solved by Haitians, not foreigners. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>, the armed forces commander, ousted civilian President <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> in June and sent him into exile. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> headed a three-man junta that had ruled <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> for two years after dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> fled the country during violent protests in February 1986. <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> now lives in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.
