<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--China-Fires     08-08 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--China-Fires,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Fires In China Kill 69 In First Half of 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forest fires killed 69 people and injured 116 in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> during the first half of the year, but the deaths represented a sharp drop from the same period a year ago, a newspaper reported today. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Headquarters </ORGANIZATION> attributed the improved record to more rain in the north and stepped-up efforts to upgrade the nation's fire-fighting capabilities, the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily said. The number of deaths declined 48 percent over the same period last year, the unidentified official was quoted as saying. The official said there were 9,700 forest fires during the first half of the year, 33 percent fewer than for the same period of 1987; and that 120,694 acres of forest were burned through June, down 85 percent, the paper reported.
