<FIRST>r i PM-China-Zoo     08-08 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Zoo,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Price Hikes Afflict Beijing Zoo Residents, Too</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elephants at the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Zoo have forgotten the taste of bananas and tigers are now rarely thrown a live chicken. Hard times have befallen their keepers. The official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said today that the 3,000 animals, birds and fish at <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest zoo have come across lean days because of inadequate funding and sharp rises in food prices. With the quadrupling of banana prices in recent years, elephants have been put on a diet of nutritious but less palatable carrots, zoo officials said. Tigers now get just two meals a day, down from three, and are fasting one day a week, zoo officials said, explaining that the big cats are used to eating irregularly in the wild. In addition, tigers, lions and other carnivores that used to have a twice-weekly treat of a live chicken or rabbit now feast on such delicacies only when they are sick or weak. The report said the zoo had to give away its most popular seal because it could n't afford the annual expense of up to $ 13,500 in fish. `` We do n't want to adopt these cruel measures, but as our budget is tightened, there seems to be no other way around,'' the report quoted <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hongtao </PERSON>, office director of the zoo, as saying. The daily said expenses at the zoo have shot up from $ 1.1 million in 1984 to $ 1.9 million last year. The state last year provided $ 810,000, and the zoo had to make up the rest by introducing video games, bumper cars and other sources of recreation. Admission to the zoo costs less than a nickel. The zoo's chief accountant, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qingchuan </PERSON>, said expenses may double next year because of swiftly rising food costs. Consumer prices rose 19 percent in June compared to the same month in 1987, while prices of some food items have nearly doubled in the past year with the elimination of some government price controls. The zoo opened in 1908 and is home to rare animals such as the giant panda and the golden monkey. It is one of the capital's main tourist attractions.
</TEXT>
