<FIRST>r a PM-PollMethod     08-08 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll Method,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-Civil Rights, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General-Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> poll on civil rights was based on telephone interviews June 22-July 2 with 1,223 adults in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Phone numbers were selected randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult at each household who had the most recent birthday. The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the sample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that if every adult American were asked the same questions, the results theoretically would be within 3 points of the poll's results, 19 times out of 20. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ 9 points, for example, for blacks, who made up 11 percent of the adjusted sample, their share of the adult population. There are other sources of potential error in polls, including the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and responses in this poll; because of rounding, some totals may exceed 100: 1. Overall, do you think blacks and other minorities have the same opportunities as whites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or not? Yes: 54 percent. No: 42 percent. Do n't know or no answer: 4 percent. 2. In the past 25 years, do you think the country has moved closer to equal opportunity among the races, or farther away from it, or has there been no movement? Closer: 84 percent. Farther: 5 percent. No movement: 7 percent. DK-NA: 4 percent. 3. Do you think it is possible to achieve equal opportunity among the races in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or not? Yes: 71 percent. No: 24 percent. DK-NA: 5 percent. 3a. If yes: Do you think it will happen in your lifetime, or not? Yes: 53 percent. No: 40 percent. DK-NA: 7 percent. 4. Do you think blacks and other minorities should receive preference in hiring to make up for past inequalities, or not? Yes: 15 percent. No: 79 percent. DK-NA: 6 percent. 5. Do you think blacks and other minorities should receive preference in college admissions to make up for past inequalities, or not? Yes: 18 percent. No: 76 percent. DK-NA: 5 percent. 6. Do you think blacks and other minorities receive equal treatment as whites in the criminal justice system, or not? Yes: 43 percent. No: 43 percent. DK-NA: 15 percent. 6a. If no: Do you think blacks and other minorities are denied justice because of their race, or not? Yes: 69 percent. No: 24 percent. DK-NA: 7 percent. 7. Do you think <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination advanced the cause of civil rights, set back the cause of civil rights, or had no effect on it? Advanced: 51 percent. Set back: 7 percent. No effect: 33 percent. DK-NA: 9 percent. 8. Do you have any close friends who are black, or not? Among whites: Yes: 67 percent. No: 31 percent. DK-NA: 2 percent. 9. Do you have any close friends who are white, or not? Among blacks Yes: 94 percent. No: 5 percent. DK-NA: 2 percent. 10. Do you think American society overall is racist, or not? Yes: 55 percent. No: 37 percent. DK-NA: 9 percent.
</TEXT>
