<HEAD>GOP Delegates Aren't Choosy on Vice President Selection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates to the Republican National Convention are n't particularly choosy about a vice presidential candidate, with the largest group inclined to accept anyone <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> selects. In an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> survey, the `` candidate'' backed by the largest group of delegates, 39 percent, was nobody in particular. Two former presidential candidates, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, each were favored by 14 percent. Others mentioned by a smattering of delegates included <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, major league baseball Commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> communications director <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON> and a couple of otherwise unknowns whose candidacies were advanced by relatives who happen to be delegates Of the 1,274 <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> delegates responding to the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> survey, 492 said they had no particular choice for the No. 2 spot on the party's ticket That sentiment is not at all uncommon as delegates tend to defer to whatever decision their party's presidential nominee makes on the issue of a running mate. Two-thirds of the Democratic delegates did not name anyone as their choice for vice president, but when <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> picked <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as his running mate, that decision was endorsed by acclamation at last month's convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he will not announce his running mate until Aug. 18, the final day of the Republican convention. The <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> survey did show some sentiment for a female vice presidential candidate. Polls have shown that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lags behind <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> among female voters, and 10 percent of the delegates responding to the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> survey said one way to overcome this would be to pick a woman as his running mate. Fourteen percent of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> delegates scattered their support among four women: former <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Ambassador <PERSON> Jeane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkpatrick </PERSON>, who was named by 82 delegates, former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, supported by 79 delegates, Sen. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> with 17 delegates and <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> with five delegates. <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON> has said she does not want to be considered for the vice presidential spot, as has <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>, who was named as the choice of two dozen delegates. The delegates' vice presidential choices cut across lines of education, gender and political experience, with roughly the same percentages of college graduates supporting <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> as <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, for example. The survey was conducted by <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> bureaus in all 50 states, as well as <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and is based on responses from 56 percent of the 2,277 delegates who will attend the GOP convention.
