<HEAD>8-8-88 Sparks Weddings, Parties, Business Openings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese throughout <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> today celebrated an auspicious once-in-a-century date _ 8-8-88 _ with a wave of weddings, business openings and lavish parties. Some hospitals geared up for maternity ward gridlock as women sought to bring their children into the world on the propitious day. And merchants spared no effort to use the date to promote everything from fast food to real estate, while <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gamblers tested their luck in a special lottery with a sweetened jackpot. Cantonese-speaking Chinese, who represent the vast majority of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s 5.7 million people and have large communities in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, have long considered eight to bring good fortune. In the Cantonese dialect, the word for eight is `` baat,'' which sounds like `` faat,'' the word for prosperity. That similarity of sound makes Aug. 8, 1988, a momentous occasion for superstitious Chinese. `` Not only the Cantonese, but everyone is celebrating,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> at the Pure Mind, one of many restaurants reporting record bookings for dinner in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, where more than one-third of the 16 million people are ethnic Chinese. The big event in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> was a ceremony atop the new <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> local headquarters to mark placement of the final beam in the 1,221-foot structure, which contractors claim is the tallest building outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the fifth-tallest in the world. Dignitaries assembled on the 70th floor to split a roast pig and a keg of sake to celebrate the occasion. In <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, at least five buildings held official openings today, including the 920-foot <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Many couples figured the best way to ensure a life of marital bliss was to get married today. The <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> government reported 278 couples registered to get married today, a 130 percent increase from a week earlier. Scores more tied the knot in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, where a mass ceremony called `` Wedding Of The Century'' was held at <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> Theater Restaurant. In <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Subang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and other hospitals reported nurses and doctors were asked to work overtime because of expectant mothers wanting to give birth today, even if the birth had to be induced. Malaysian doctors, speaking on condition of anonymity, said women with Caesarean sections scheduled for other days this week had asked that the procedure be done today. Businessmen, meanwhile, launched every conceivable promotion to mark the date. In <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, one real estate agent offered `` a lucky discount'' of 8,888 <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> dollars -LRB- $ 4,356.86 -RRB- on a three-story house. A <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> restaurant in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> offered 88 children who turned 8 this month a meal as well as T-shirts sporting `` 8888.'' Several <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> hotels ran promotions tied to the date. Diners at the Loong Yuen Chinese Restaurant at the Holiday Inn Golden Mile ate for free if their total bill included four 8s. The colony's lottery also held a special drawing today with a jackpot enlarged by an additional 3,888,888 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> dollars -LRB- nearly $ 500,000 -RRB-. Despite all the hoopla, local astrologers who consult the traditional Chinese calendar dismissed suggestions that today was the century's luckiest day. `` It is a good day, but not a special one,'' sniffed astrologer `` Rocky'' Sung Siu-kwong of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in a recent interview. Indeed, today's scheduled opening of a new light-rail mass transit system in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> was put off after a spate of test-run accidents, including one that killed an 8-year-old boy. Little luck rubbed off on the colony's free-wheeling stock exchange, where prices dropped slightly in light trading. In <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lumpur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, however, the commodity exchange launched trading in cocoa futures to coincide with the date. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Yue </PERSON>, a self-described master of geomancy, palmistry, astrology and name consultant in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, cautioned that 8-8-88 may not mean prosperity for all. He noted the Cantonese pronounciation for four is `` sei,'' the same as the word that means to die. Since today's date has four eights, he advised: `` Tread with caution and contain your greed.''
