<SECOND>PM-Crater Vents,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Dives Exciting, But No Hot Springs Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRATER LAKE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists' first dives to the bottom of <LOCATION> Crater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> turned up no signs of expected hot springs that might be evidence of ancient volcanic activity, but their submarine ride gave them a new outlook. `` I think so far we have seen similar things, but in much greater detail than last year,'' when a robot submarine explored the lake, <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> oceanographer <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Dymond </PERSON> said Sunday, describing the first two dives. `` We have n't found any actual thermal springs,'' said <PERSON> Dymond </PERSON>, who made the first manned dive to the bottom of the nation's deepest lake Friday The deepest point in the lake is 1,932 feet. <PERSON> Dymond </PERSON> and fellow <ORGANIZATION> OSU </ORGANIZATION> oceanographer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> are using a one-man submersible called Deep Rover to search the lake for hot springs that may be the remnants of volcanic activity that formed the lake. <PERSON> Dymond </PERSON> said he saw what he interpreted as evidence of old hot springs: deposits of iron and manganese and rock formations with colored stains on holes or cracks. The research could affect efforts by <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to develop hydrothermal energy nearby, outside the boundary of Crater Lake National Park. If the lake is found to have significant geothermal features, development in the neighboring <ORGANIZATION> Winema </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> could be prohibited. The two men are in the second year of a three-year effort financed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to learn why the lake's water is so clear, with visibility measured to depths of 85 to 115 feet. <PERSON> Collier </PERSON>, who made his first dive Saturday, said that at a depth of 1,200 feet blue light was still visible from above. Their work is part of a larger 10-year study started after scientists in the 1970s noticed a significant reduction in the lake's clarity. Recent measurements have shown the clarity returning to levels last measured in the 1930s. <PERSON> Dymond </PERSON> and <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> said nothing they have found so far could settle the question of whether drilling for hydrothermal energy more than seven miles away would affect the lake. <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> geologist <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFleur </PERSON> said if hot springs do exist, they would n't be affected by the drilling. Crater Lake was formed after rain and melted snow filled a crater, called a caldera, formed when the <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mazama </LOCATION> volcano erupted nearly 7,000 years ago and then collapsed into what had been a chamber filled with molten rock. <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dymond </PERSON> said sonar echos off unexpectedly craggy features on the bottom of the lake made precise navigation difficult. Precise navigation is important. Last year, while using the remote-controlled submersible, scientists found what looked like a vent oozing a milky fluid. However, they were never able to relocate it to take a temperature reading or a fluid sample.
