<TEXT>
 The government today declared an immediate cease-fire in the 13-year Angolan war and set Nov. 1 as the date it plans to begin pulling out of neighboring <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. However, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said further negotiations are necessary to determine a timetable for withdrawal of Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and the granting of independence to <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. `` This is the first step of a very long, arduous road to peace,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> told a news conference. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also were expected to issue statements today following last week's fifth round of U.S.-mediated peace talks. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> planned to pull its estimated 3,000 troops out of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> by Sept. 1. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, along with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, backs the <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebel movement in its 13-year-old fight against the Angolan government. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> is backed by an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has an estimated 50,000 troops in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said withdrawal would begin Nov. 1. But he said the countries involved must first agree on a single date for the total withdrawal of Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The parties plan a sixth round of talks the week of Aug. 22 to try to resolve the matter. The site of the talks was not announced. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said it will grant <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independence next June 1 if all Cuban forces have left <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> by that date. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, however, has offered in previous talks to withdraw over four years. Today's announcement suggested the two sides were closer to agreeing on a mutual date than at any time previously. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> had invited <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to discuss Namibian independence. `` It's imperative that the secretary general visit <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> urgently,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. The peace talks began in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in May. In the fifth round, held last week in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, negotiators reportedly agreed on a cease-fire between South African and Cuban-Angolan forces as well as a mutual pullback of troops. Details of the agreement were withheld. The parties have reached no public agreement on the role of <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the main black group fighting white rule in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has called for the dismantling of seven guerrilla camps it says are operated in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> by the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s mandate over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> was terminated by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1966, but it has retained control over the territory in defiance of several <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolutions. The state-run South African <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, in a commentary today, described the current diplomatic climate as `` one that would hardly have been conceivable just a few months ago.'' However, it said major problems remained unresolved in regard to implementation of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan for elections in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. `` The very substantial costs associated with the plan have caught some of the parties unawares,'' the report said. `` Apart from the $ 600 million needed for organizing U.N.-sponsored elections, guarantees will have to be found for replacing the $ 120 million -LRB- in -RRB- annual economic aid ... that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has borne until now.''
