<HEAD>Bush Blasts Democrats, Suggests Reagan May Appear With Him at
Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush comments, prepared remarks in top 12 grafs,
picking up in 5th graf pvs, The Bush; cuts last 6 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLELANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> criticized the Democrats' platform as `` a document of deceit'' today and suggested there still may be a chance that he and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will appear together at the Republican National Convention next week Initial plans called for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to leave <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> returns next Tuesday. However, the vice president told reporters on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> II that he would view such a joint appearance as a plus for his campaign. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, trying to put his stamp on the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> platform, flew to the Republicans' convention city today to call for `` a statement of solutions'' that he said would cotrast with the invisible policies of rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` He's the stealth candidate,'' the vice president said in prepared remarks. `` For while he ca n't decide about the stealth bomber, he favors instead stealth policies _ they can be neither seen nor heard.'' `` His campaign jets from place to place, but no issues show up on the radar screen.'' Besides testifying before the platform committee, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was also to tour the Superdome, where he will be formally nominated next week as his party's presidential candidate. `` Their nominee spoke for 50 minutes in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and failed to mention the most important issue of our time: how to make the world a safer place,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` We need to make this campaign a plan for the future, a statement of solutions, not an exercise in evasion,'' he said. `` We should make our principles and our policies crystal clear to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ran through a litany of positions he had espoused during his campaign, suggesting their inclusion in the platform. These ranged from tax credits for child care to a ban on offshore dumping, a reduction in the capital gains tax and imposition of the death penalty for drug kingpins. `` If we want to stop our kids from putting drugs in their veins, they must first have good ideas in their heads and moral character in their hearts,'' he said. On Sunday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke with reporters on the grounds of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, after attending services with 22 members of his family: his wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>; his 87-year-old mother, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON>; his five adult children, their spouses and his 10 grandchildren The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> clan, which occupied the two front pews of the small oceanfront church, later posed for family photographs outside and taped television commercials for the fall campaign. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> denied accusations from the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign that he was shying away from debates. `` Not only do I want debates, but I have to because I've got to get him to stand by his record,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` We've got to spell these differences out and debates are a good way to do it,'' he said But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was vague on when _ and how often _ he would be willing to debate <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` There'll be more than one debate, but how many ... has not been sorted out yet,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was only making a display of bravado for the television cameras and should agree to debate Sept. 14 in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, the first of three dates set by a bipartisan commission. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign officials have criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for refusing to commit himself to the schedule of debates set by the advisory commission. `` It's time to dock the motorboat in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION> and launch the debate in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON> said Sunday. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s designated campaign chairman, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, suggested <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> might further distance himself from positions embraced by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration once he is formally nominated. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who is resigning his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post next week, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already has started to develop his `` own individual persona.'' `` He will be seen in an entirely different light once he is his party's nominee, a bit more free to speak out, speak his own mind, and speak out on issues distinct and different from the administration,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Meet the Press.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> also said he did not view <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign as troubled _ despite low ratings in recent public opinion polls. `` But I would agree there are a large number of unfavorables out there,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. He suggested the gap corresponded to the `` disapproval rating of the administration, of the president'' and that it would narrow as the election approaches.
