<HEAD>Team Begins Unloading Toxic Waste From Syrian Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENOA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Experts began work Monday to unload from a Syrian ship 12,000 drums of a toxic substance that shippers have been trying to dispose of for more than a year. Several rusty, leaking drums from the freighter Zanoobia were being put into larger containers while experts began tests on the waste, said <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Francese </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Genoa </LOCATION> port. Unloading the drums will take from two to three months, he said. The Zanoobia brought the waste back to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> two months ago after foreign countries refused to accept it. The Italian state-controlled company <ORGANIZATION> Castalia </ORGANIZATION>, which won a $ 6 million contract to dispose of the waste, did not make public the final destination of the unidentified toxic material, although port sources said the material may be sent abroad to be incinerated. The waste, produced by Italian firms, was returned to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> after unsuccessful attempts to dump it in <LOCATION> Djibouti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>.
