<HEAD>Forecasters Eyeing Tropical Depression Over Southeast Louisiana</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with noon EDT position on Beryl, Alberto
dissolving off the Canadian coast.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical storm <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON>, the second named storm of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, hugged the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> coast today, forcing evacuations from oil rigs in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, while the season's first tropical storm fizzled out near the Canadian coast. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> was upgraded today from a tropical depression after its winds strengthened, reaching close to 45 mph with gusts up to 55 mph. The storm strengthened as it drifted closer to the warm waters of the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Oil companies evacuated more than 2,000 workers from oil rigs in southern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and the Gulf. The tropical storm had a center near latitude 29.5 north and longitude 89.3 west. It was drifting southeastward at less than 5 mph, and its movement was expected to be slow and erratic through Tuesday. The storm's center was about 50 miles southeast of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. `` There is some likelihood it could strengthen,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> of the National Hurricane Center in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` It's not drifting inland, it's drifting away from land, but very slowly.'' <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> said the immediate danger from <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> was to shipping and oil rigs along the Gulf coast. People on the coast, he said, should watch for tides of up to three feet above normal. Tropical storm warnings were in effect from <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and small craft from <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> O'Connor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, eastward to <LOCATION> Appalachicola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, should remain in port, the center said. `` Right now we're advising people to listen to their radios and watch television,'' said <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Valence </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, about 40 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` It's highly unusual for depressions to form over land. Most of the time they get their start way out in the middle of the ocean,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>, a forecaster at the National Hurricane Center in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` We do n't have a lot of experience with systems that form this way.'' A tropical weather system becomes a named storm when its winds hit 39 mph, and a hurricane when wind velocity reaches 74 mph. The storm chiefly affected those out on oil rigs in the Gulf, the weather service said. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifa </PERSON> said about 2,000 workers were being evacuated early today. All employees at facilities at <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leesville </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Plaquemines </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> were evacuated by boat and helicopter, while non-essential personnel were removed from a facility at <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lifa </PERSON> said the storm became more threatening as it neared the gulf. `` News reports -LRB- over the weekend -RRB- were that the center was partially onshore and partially offshore, so we did n't have high winds to worry about,'' <PERSON> Lifa </PERSON> said. `` The concern is that the more it gets into the gulf, the more winds pick up. It is something we are very concerned about.'' <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Hebert </PERSON> said an unknown number of workers were taken off <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> rigs in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> today. Coast Guard Petty Officer First Class <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Morehead </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has not carried out any evacuations, but the storm's winds buffeted helicopters and created choppy seas for its ships The storm did n't appear to affect Republicans gathering in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> for their national convention next week; about 2 percent, or 105, of the delegates have arrived to serve on various pre-convention panels and committees, said <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Thumma </PERSON>, co-director of media operations for the convention. `` Better this week than next week,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, the convention manager. The storm was unlikely to have any effect on today's visit by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who landed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> this morning for an appearance at <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> platform sessions, said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also planned a stop at the Superdome, site of the convention. `` Right now <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> is mostly getting the weaker western side of the storm. The folks that have been getting the worst of it are those south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>,'' said meteorologist <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Koziara </PERSON>. Meanwhile <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON>, the season's first named storm, fizzled out today off the Canadian coast, <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> said. `` It's lost its tropical characteristics,'' he said. `` Now it's just a storm. The center will no longer issue bulletins on it, he said. Shortly after noon Sunday, the forecasters had issued a tropical storm warning for <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s coast from <LOCATION> Bar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Eastport </LOCATION>, but they canceled it less than six hours later. The storm was most likely to make landfall at <LOCATION> Yarmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Halifax </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Eddy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>, forecasters said. Typically, there are 10 named storms during the six-month hurricane season, which begins June 1. Last year, there were only three hurricanes and four tropical storms in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>.
