<HEAD>Thousands of Vagrants Warned or Arrested in Byelorussia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities in the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> have arrested or given official warnings for vagrancy to more than 40,000 people in the past four years, a newspaper report said. The report in Saturday's <LOCATION> Sovietskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION>, received Monday in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said more than half of the people arrested for vagrancy had held jobs but either were fired or quit voluntarily when they started wandering. The newspaper added that many others had lost families and homes while imprisoned and are faced with a suspicious society that does not want to give them a second chance. `` Being isolated from society, many of them lose their families, their residence permits, homes, and when they return work collectives often do not wish to accept them and recognize them as first-class citizens,'' the report said. Soviet media have begun paying more attention to social problems such as homelessness and vagrancy in the more open atmosphere created by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost. The numbers cited by <LOCATION> Sovietskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> _ 8,000 arrests and 35,000 warnings _ were surprisingly large for the republic of 10 million people. There was no indication how they might compare with figures in other areas of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> guarantees a job and a place to live for all of its citizens, and proclaims that as one of the benefits of the Soviet system. The newspaper said many of the vagrants turn to theft of government or personal property. More than 80 percent of the vagrants are men, the newspaper said. Three - quarters of the men and half of the women are under 30 Half have a high school education, but every sixth vagrant has specialized high school or technical training, it said.
