<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors Check Cruise Missile Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet inspectors arrived Monday to visit a cruise missile base and a repair shop to check compliance with the superpower treaty to remove ground-launched medium-range nuclear missiles from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the 20 Soviets on Tuesday will visit <LOCATION> Florennes </LOCATION> air base, 40 miles south of here and a Belgian plant, 10 miles north of <LOCATION> Florennes </LOCATION>, which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> uses as a repair and maintenance shop for its European-based cruise missiles. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has deployed 20 cruise missiles at <LOCATION> Florennes </LOCATION> and 55 cruise missiles and their launch canisters are at the plant at <LOCATION> Gosselies </LOCATION> which belongs to <ORGANIZATION> Sabca </ORGANIZATION>, an aviation construction company. The Soviet inspectors, led by <PERSON> Viacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyebedev </PERSON>, arrived at <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>' Abelag airport and were welcomed by Belgian officials; <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fer </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s European field office at <LOCATION> Rhein-Main </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>; and his deputy, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Army Lt. <PERSON> Col </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>. Under the U.S.-Soviet accord, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will remove all ground-launched nuclear missiles with a range of between 300 and 3,400 miles. The treaty, which removes an entire class of nuclear arms, said <PERSON> Lyebedev </PERSON>, `` marks the beginning of an unprecedented stage in the history of mankind.'' `` We will perform our duties in strict compliance with the provisions of the treaty,'' said <PERSON> Lyebedev </PERSON>, speaking through an interpreter. <PERSON> Fer </PERSON> said the inspections `` are serious business. It is a task we accept with commitment.'' In recent weeks, Soviet inspectors have visited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile sites and related installations in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> is the only European nation not yet visited by Soviet inspectors. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors have already visited sites in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. The Florennes air base houses the 485th <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Tactical Missile Wing. Under <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s 1979 decision to deploy 572 cruise and Pershing-2 missiles in the five European nations, 48 cruise missiles were to be based at <LOCATION> Florennes </LOCATION>. The repair plant at <LOCATION> Gosselies </LOCATION> belongs to the Belgian firm of <ORGANIZATION> Sabca </ORGANIZATION>, a Belgiasn aviation construction firm, and does maintenance and control checks on unarmed missiles from <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Under the treaty, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to remove hundreds of ground-launched medium - and shorter-range missiles in a three-year period and not to produce or test such weapons after that The treaty also gives each party on-site inspection rights for 13 years. The treaty covers <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise, Pershing-1A and Pershing-2 missiles and Soviet SS-20, SS-4, SS-5, SS-12 and SS-23 missiles.
