<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday that a new valve had tested out satisfactorily in the space shuttle Discovery's engine compartment and they rescheduled the ship's oft-postponed main engine test firing for Wednesday The countdown for the test will begin at 6:10 p.m. EDT Tuesday. The 22-second engine firing is set for 7:30 a.m. The engine test was halted Thursday in the last second when a sensor reported that a valve had not closed as it was supposed to. Engineers determined that the sensor, not the valve, was malfunctioning but decided to replace both parts as a unit. That required erecting scaffolding, removing extensive plumbing and wiring and gaining access to the crowded engine compartment. The changeout was completed by midnight Saturday. The work of reconnecting and testing all parts and removing the work platforms was being completed Monday. `` Work on changing the hydrogen fuel bleed valve in Discovery's number two main engine went better than expected over the weekend,'' the space agency announced Monday, in setting the new test date `` The recovery from the problem on Thursday shows that the team is working smoothly and I am expecting an on-time engine firing on Wednesday morning,'' said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s Kennedy Space Center All three of Discovery's engines will be fired, using only a portion of the half million gallons of fuel in the external tank, while the shuttle remains bolted to the launch pad. The two solid fuel rocket boosters flanking the shuttle tank will not be ignited. In the past, a flight readiness firing has been required only for new shuttles, except for one time when a malfunction made a retest necessary. But the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is treating Discovery as an untried ship because of the long time since the last flight and the many changes made since the Challenger disaster. Challenger exploded 73 seconds after launch on Jan. 28, 1986, with the loss of seven lives and there have been no American manned missions since then. A leak in Challenger's right booster was blamed for the accident. The boosters have been redesigned to prevent a recurrence. Discovery's test-firing has been postponed five times for various malfunctions, including leaks in ground equipment and last wee's abort. No date has been set for Discovery's four-day flight with five astronauts aboard, but the delays have made it all but certain that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> ca n't meet a late September target.
