<HEAD>Railroad Tie Eliminated As Cause, Wake Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities investigating a boat racing accident that injured 23 spectators eliminated a floating railroad tie as the cause Monday, leaving the wake from other boats as the prime explanation. Early reports suggested the boat driven by 1987 Canadian <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Champion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> struck the railroad tie. `` There's no connection,'' said Public Safety Director <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>. `` There are no marks on it at all to indicate that it was struck by anything, and we have a witness who places it near the shore before the impact occurred.'' <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>'s boat, which was clocked at more than 116 mph during time trials for the Champion Spark Plug Grand Prix event, catapulted out of the <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, veered right and crashed into the bank, where spectators were watching the 11th annual Three Rivers Regatta. `` It just seems he hit a wake,'' <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. `` It lifted him up in the air. When it came down it did n't come down in the manner it should have. He tried to steer the boat to the left.'' <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, who suffered minor injuries and shock, told police he believed his boat was buffeted by air from the boats he was following. Investigators hoped to determine the speed by studying videotape of the scene shot from a blimp for <LOCATION> Secaucus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, television station <ORGANIZATION> WWOR </ORGANIZATION>. The station was covering the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mets-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pirates </ORGANIZATION> baseball game nearby at Three Rivers stadium. The boat appeared to slow after it veered toward shore, apparently no longer under power. `` Not only that, but as he hit, the bottom of the engine would have begun striking the bottom of the river,'' <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. `` And there's a man-made edge, called riprap, stones together with cement, that slowed the boat tremendously.'' Divers continued looking Monday for the last missing piece of the boat, a piece of metal that was located below the propeller. The part could confirm whether debris in the river contributed to the accident, <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, city officials started reviewing crowd control measures. The <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> previously used fence to keep spectators from the river's edge, but `` for some reason ... that was discontinued,'' <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. The fence will probably be back next year, putting an additional 15 to 20 feet of concrete walkway between the water and spectators, he said. Only one of the injured remained in critical condition Monday, said <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>. Two others improved to serious, seven remained hospitalized in serious to good condition, and 13 others were released.
