<HEAD>Governors Applaud Vintage Reagan Speech on Big Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's governors warmly applauded President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Monday for a vintage attack on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and a tribute to their initiatives in dealing with national issues such as welfare and job creation. `` He was talking language we understand,'' Republican Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> said of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s address to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> replied, `` Absolutely,'' when asked if he thought it was a political speech designed to help Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the presidential campaign. `` But it was one that was appropriate within the limits of the association,'' <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> added. `` I think it was as political as he could be without stepping out of line.'' Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, the association's most prominent current member, was not present for the president's speech The Democratic presidential candidate planned to attend the closing session of the <ORGANIZATION> NGA </ORGANIZATION> meeting on Tuesday and then have a closed strategy session with <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> governors. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> never mentioned <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or the presidential campaign, but he touted the economic statistics certain to be a key part of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign. `` Our states, like our citizens, have known the blessings of the longest peacetime economic expansion on record,'' he told the governors, citing the creation of more than 17 million jobs during his two terms as well as a current unemployment rate that is the lowest in 14 years. The largest part of the president's speech was devoted to citing the virtues of states as opposed to the federal government _ a familiar theme of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency. `` In the last seven and one-half years we have broken the federal government of its compulsion to control every breath the states take,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. He said that `` too often in the past when <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> listened to the states, it heard only what it wanted to hear. Today, things are different. When governors talk, we not only listen, but we hear.'' Praising state initiatives, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that `` from education, to transportation, to helping <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s poor and homeless, you have led. While <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been caught up in partisan intrigue, you've gone out and done the job.'' The governors were meeting between the two national political conventions, but they studiously avoided allowing the campaign to intrude on their meeting. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> held to that non-partisan approach. But he was far more partisan during a stop at <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Precision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lens </ORGANIZATION>, a firm located a few miles from the governors meeting. Still avoiding mentioning <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by name, the president said, `` I've heard some people bad mouthing our economy recently. I think they must have stopped reading the newspaper that day in 1981 when they handed over the lease to the White House.'' He said `` some people are telling you to take for granted the economic growth of today and of the last seven years.'' He characterized that message as telling people `` you can take prosperity for granted, it's time for a change, take a chance on us.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that was `` sort of like someone telling you that you've stored up all the cold beer you could want, so now you can unplug the refrigerator. ... You ca n't unplug our pro-growth economic policies and expect things to stay the same.'' Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> retorted that `` the issue is bread and butter, not cold beer.'' <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> called <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech to the governors `` a wonderful trip down memory lane. ... All of us would agree on the importance of initiatives on the state level.'' <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would be a help to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, but `` anybody, no matter how good they are, is a marginal help. It's up to the candidate who's running.''
