<HEAD>Felix Leclerc Dies At 74</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Leclerc </PERSON>, a singer, poet and playwright, died Monday at his home of a heart attack, a family spokesman said. He was 74. <PERSON> Leclerc </PERSON> had been ill for some time, said his secretary, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Jobin </PERSON>. Born in La Tuque, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leclerc </PERSON> was best known for writing nationalist songs that influenced such <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> singers as <PERSON> Gilles </PERSON> <PERSON> Vigneault </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Charlebois </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Julien </PERSON>. <PERSON> Leclerc </PERSON> lived on the Ile-d'Orleans, an island in the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Survivors include his wife and two children.
