<SECOND>AM-Justice-American,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Airlines To Pay $70,000 To Settle Discrimination
Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 70,000 to resolve a government complaint that it discriminated against flight attendant applicants based on their citizenship status, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The settlement will cost the air carrier $ 53,000 in back pay and $ 17,000 in federal civil penalties. The agreement will affect 33 applicants who qualified as `` intending citizens,'' but whom <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> refused to consider for employment _ either because they could not produce an alien registration card or because their cards had expiration dates. `` Intending citizens'' under the 1986 immigration law are permanent and temporary residents admitted under the new legalization program, and refugees and those who have sought asylum who intend to become citizens. The act prohibits employers from discriminating against them. `` We hope this settlement will put others in the airline industry on notice that the challenged practices are proscribed by the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Siskind </PERSON>, the special counsel named under the statute. <PERSON> Siskind </PERSON>'s office enforces prohibitions against employment discrimination based on national origin and citizenship status. The agreement settles a complaint filed April 12 and can not be construed as an admission of liability by American, the department said.
