<HEAD>`L.A. Law' Star Reveals Breast Cancer; Will Do NBC Documentary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON> revealed Monday that she was undergoing treatment for breast cancer while filming the first six episodes of the hit <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> series `` L.A. Law'' two years ago. <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON> made a surprise appearance at a news conference held by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON> to announce she will help produce with NBC News a documentary about breast cancer survivors, `` Destined to Survive: 100 Roads to Recovery,'' to air Oct. 12. `` I was one of the lucky ones. I did n't have to lose a breast,'' said <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON>, who said the cancer was discovered between filming of the pilot and beginning of production of the series. `` I had to undergo radiation therapy during the first six episodes of ` <LOCATION> L.A </LOCATION>. Law.' It was not an easy time,'' she said. <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON> plays attorney <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelsey </PERSON> on the series. She and co-star <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> are married in real life as well as on the series. `` Between the period of my treatment and diagnosis, I underwent a tremendous amount of soul-searching and terror, despite the incredible support of my husband, my family and my friends,'' said <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON>. `` The only real rays of hope came from the women who had been through these things and survived. They were the ones who made me feel I was n't alone.'' The documentary will profile 100 survivors of breast cancer, some famous, such as first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and others not. The aim is to encourage other women to carefully check themselves for signs of the disease. `` We brought this project to <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> because we felt, I felt he would be sympathetic because of his history with <PERSON> Hodgkin </PERSON>'s disease, because he's also destined to live,'' <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON> said he underwent successful treatment of <PERSON> Hodgkin </PERSON>'s disease, a form of cancer, several years ago before he went on to huge success programming <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s prime-time lineup `` When <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> brought this to me it honestly did touch a chord,'' he said. `` I do think that what this will say to people who face any form of cancer, particularly breast cancer, is that you can not only survive, you can triumph, flourish and lead meaningful, productive lives.''
