<FIRST>u a AM-WritersStrike Bjt   08-08 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Writers Strike, Bjt,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hollywood Goes Back To Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Months behind in an industry where everything is due last week, producers and scriptwriters scrambled Monday to regroup after a 22-week strike that idled thousands and devastated the fall television schedule. The Writers Guild of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> membership Sunday voted 2,111 to 412, or by 83.7 percent, in favor of the pact with the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>. `` I would say nobody's in fighting form,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON> said. The walkout crippled <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and left the upcoming TV season in shambles. The season's start will be delayed, perhaps until mid-October or later, despite the anticipated glut of written material. The production season for prime-time television usually begins in late June and early July. `` What we are going to do this morning is what we normally do in May. We have two writers' meetings today and three tomorrow,'' producer <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said in a telephone interview as he drove to work. `` We are starting from scratch, which is what everyone in town is doing.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, producer of TV's `` Beauty and the <LOCATION> Beast </LOCATION>,'' `` The Golden Girls,'' `` It's A Living'' and `` Empty Nest,'' said the networks have not reduced their orders, and he expects to produce 22 shows for `` Beauty and the Beast'' and `` The Golden Girls.'' `` Probably around the production of the fourth and fifth episode we will start to feel the crunch because of lack of planning and have to start spending more money,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. `` You're always behind in TV, and that will just happen sooner.'' The ratification came in the 154th day of one of the longest and most painful strikes in modern Hollywood history, eclipsing by one day the <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION>'s 1960 walkout that lasted 153 days. `` There have been hardships,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolla </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, which is holding its annual conference in <LOCATION> Reno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, this week. <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolla </PERSON> said the five-month strike resulted in the worst unemployment rate in the history of his union, which covers carpenters, electricians, set decorators, costumers and other crafts. Of the 75,000-member union, up to 60 percent were unemployed, <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolla </PERSON> said. One-third of the union's members are based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wurtz </PERSON> and his writing partner, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Benest </PERSON>, have two television movies for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and two feature films for 20th Century Fox that will all be due in coming weeks. `` Today, we're starting on the second draft of one of the TV movies,'' <PERSON> Wurtz </PERSON> said. `` And we have to deliver a second draft on one of the features within six weeks.'' <PERSON> Wurtz </PERSON> said he typically writes four to five hours in the morning and devotes afternoons to business. `` Now, I might be working eight to 10 hours a day writing, and I may be working more than five days a week.'' At restaurants and messenger services, two peripheral businesses affected by the strike, managers noted an upswing in business as early as last week, when a tentative agreement was reached following several days of rumor. `` Thursday and Friday we had a little burst of business,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Casado </PERSON>, who with his wife <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> owns the El Adobe Mexican restaurant on Melrose Avenue across the street from <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>. `` I look forward to things improving. Beside the writers, you have all the extras. And the carpenters and electricians, those guys eat pretty good too,'' <PERSON> Casado </PERSON> said. `` It may take awhile. They may need a few checks to get back ahead of things.'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> LA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> messenger service, also said business had picked up Thursday and Friday. Before the strike, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> LA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> dealt almost exclusively with entertainment industry clients and suffered a 50 percent loss in business. He said he pushed for new, non-entertainment clients and recouped about 90 percent of his regular business `` Now we hope to go through the roof,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION> has 9,000 members, most living and working in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The alliance has 217 member companies, responsible for 85 percent of network prime-time television and 90 percent of feature film production and distribution.
