<HEAD>Reagan May Sign Bill Increasing Industry Liability in Nuke
Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is expected to sign legislation to require nuclear power companies to take a bigger financial responsibility for damages arising from a reactor accident, an administration official said Monday. `` We have strongly supported this bill,'' the official said of the proposed 15-year renewal of the 1957 Price-Anderson Act that won final congressional approval on a voice vote Friday in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is likely that he will sign it,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The Price-Anderson Act is unique because it is the only federal statute that sets a limit on how much a company or an entire industry can be forced to pay to victims of an industrial accident. The bill would set the liability limit for the nuclear generating industry at $ 7.1 billion for all damages from a single accident. That is 10 times the amount the industry was responsible for under the previous law, which expired a year ago. If damage awards exceeded the limit, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have to come up with a legislative plan to supply the rest of the money. The $ 7.1 billion limit walks a line between the nuclear industry, which sought a lower figure, and interest groups like <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader-founded </PERSON> organization which pushed for a higher limit or none at all. Public Citizen has pointed to government studies suggesting that a catastrophic nuclear accident could cause $ 100 billion or more in damages. Critics say the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> could end up providing most of the compensation. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, national field director of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said that `` while the -LRB- new -RRB- cap is a net improvement over current law, the revision does little more than current law to encourage corporate responsibility, to protect taxpayers from having to pay for a nuclear accident or to ensure that all legitimate victims of an accident are compensated.'' <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Unglesbee </PERSON>, director of legislative communications for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group, called the legislation `` a big step forward in compensation'' for victims. Renewal of the Price-Anderson Act is not expected to spur construction of new nuclear power plants. <PERSON> Unglesbee </PERSON> says that to revive the industry, the federal licensing procedure needs to be streamlined and a standardized plant design must be established. And barring an accident requiring large payments to victims, the higher liability limit is not expected to have any major impact on electricity rates charged by utilities with nuclear plants, according to congressional aides.
