<HEAD>New Central Park Zoo Opens Amid Fanfare</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `Monkeys, bats...' with 1 graf to update with
attendance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new Central Park Zoo opened Monday amid much fanfare, with a collection of penguins, polar bears, piranhas and their pals entertaining huge crowds in their recently renovated $ 30 million home. A four-block-long line snaked through the park within an hour of the opening as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkers </LOCATION> waited for their first look at rarities such as the Golfodulcean Dart poison frog, the tufted puffin or the plumbeous water redstart -LRB- that's a bird, folks -RRB-. `` These animals know how to act. They're not like people, who have to learn how to act,'' said 11-year-old <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Benitez </PERSON>, one of the first visitors to the Tropic Zone _ one of the zoo's three new natural habitats. Monkeys, bats, fish and frogs were featured there; the Polar Circle hosts polar bears, penguins and arctic foxes; the Temperate Territory is home to otters, red pandas, turtles and sea lions. In all, 13,701 visitors toured the three areas on its first day, the <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. `` When Mayor <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> appointed me five years ago, I promised to be a man for all species,'' said Parks Commissioner <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, who introduced the 450 animals from more than 100 species. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> then cut the ribbon to officially open the new facility before playing straight man to a frisky sea lion named <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>, circling in the newly renovated sea lion tank in the middle of the park, waved to <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, waved to the visitors, caught fish tossed by the mayor and barked on request. The renovation of the zoo was supposed to cost $ 28 million, but came in at about $ 30 million, partly because work took several months longer than anticipated, <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said. Construction on the new zoo began in April 1985. `` The other zoo was like a Sing-Sing for animals,'' said <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, referring to the facility shut down in the winter of 1983. `` So we've built a humane zoo, a zoo for the 1990s.'' There was one other new feature: Visitors, who once toured for free, now pay $ 1; senior citizens pay 50 cents, while kids come through for a quarter.
