 <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> was an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> nurse in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> during World War II when she met her future husband. Five months after the war's end, she and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, a Marine officer at the time, were married. They celebrated their 42nd wedding anniversary last February. `` O'Bie'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, as she is known to friends, is a frequent traveling companion of her husband, the secretary of state, and was a passenger in <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s motorcade Monday in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, when a terrorist bomb went off. The car in which she was riding was slightly damaged but she and others in the caravan escaped injury. The Shultzes have remained a very close couple over the years, a fact amply demonstrated at the time of his appointment to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in July 1982. On arrival in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after being summoned from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> found two limousines awaiting him at the airport. One, he was told, was for him, the other for his wife to take her anywhere she wanted to go while <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> had his interview with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> waved off the second car. `` No,'' he said, `` she'll come with me. We're a package deal.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who does not tell her age, lists her special interests and hobbies as handicapped children, gardening, golf, traveling and `` taking care of and keeping up with <PERSON> George </PERSON>.'' She looks forward to the time next January when <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> returns to private life after six years at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. They have