<HEAD>Navy Successfully Tests `Capsule Launch' Cruise Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it had successfully demonstrated a submarine `` capsule launch'' system for a Tomahawk cruise missile during a test in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The test firing was performed by the nuclear-powered USS Providence on Sunday and involved a conventional land-attack version of the Tomahawk fitted into a specially added `` capsule'' in the bow of the submarine. The cruise missile _ carrying an inert warhead for the test _ was launched from the submerged submarine and then `` flew a fully guided land-attack mission of approximately 450 miles to a recovery area on the <ORGANIZATION> Eglin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, range,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said. The test was important because it demonstrated that land-attack cruise missiles can be carried and stored aboard a submarine in the bow, outside the pressure hull, and fired from that position, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>, a spokesman. Without such a capsule launch system in the bow, a submarine can not be armed with cruise missiles without reducing its arsenal of on-board torpedoes, he added.
