<HEAD>Veteran Journalist, War Hero, Dead At 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, a veteran foreign correspondent who covered <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> during more than 40 years with the wire service, died Sunday of emphysema. He was 66. At the time of his death, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> was senior correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> Maturity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, a nationally syndicated wire service covering issues affecting older Americans. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, a native New Yorker, began his journalism career as a copy boy for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and Time magazine. He joined <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, as the agency was then known, in 1941 but left to join the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in 1942. He saw action in the European theater during World War II, and received the Purple Heart and air medal with three clusters. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> was the lead radio operator-gunner with the Hell's Angels B-17 bomber squadron that operated out of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> In March 1944, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>'s plane was shot down over <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and he was rescued by French Resistance forces, who hid him for two months. German border guards captured him in the <LOCATION> Pyrenees </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> as he was attempting to reach <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. He was freed in May 1945 by British forces six days before <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> surrendered. After rejoining <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> served in bureaus in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Assignments also took him to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION>. While in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, he met and married <PERSON> Clare </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorene </PERSON> <PERSON> Brubaker </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employee at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION> European news editor from 1962 to 1972. He was the service's Asian division chief, directing the coverage of the Vietnam War, from 1972 to 1973. From 1973 until his retirement in 1987, he worked in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as head of <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION>'s national security affairs team. He is survived by his wife <PERSON> Clare </PERSON>; mother, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>; sister, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Calkin </PERSON>; and brother, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>. Burial will be in Arlington National Cemetery.
