<HEAD>House Extends Funds For Emergency Hunger Relief Through Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Monday passed an emergency hunger relief bill that extends a temporary food program for a year and requires the government to buy an extra $ 110 million in surplus commodities for the needy. The bill, similar to one passed last month by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, also makes small increases in food stamp benefits and makes it easier for farmers, the disabled and the elderly to qualify for food stamps. The measure goes to a conference committee to be reconciled with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill. The House bill, passed by voice vote, extends through fiscal 1989 the <ORGANIZATION> Temporary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> which distributes surplus agricultural commodities to the needy. The bill earmarks an extra $ 70 million for TEFAP and the remaining $ 40 million for commodities to be distributed by soup kitchens and food banks. Including the food stamp changes, the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> has estimated the bill will cost $ 306 million in fiscal 1989, rising gradually to $ 671 million in 1993. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has said it opposes the bill for budget and policy reasons.
