<HEAD>Governors Commend Drought Relief Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Relief, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farm state governors Monday approved a resolution commending the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for quick action on an aid package for farmers hit hard by the drought. The governors, in a report from a task force chaired by <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON>, also urged continued federal and state attention to the problems of farmers struggling to cope with today's economics and international trade imbalances. The Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development of the National Governors' Association unanimously approved a resolution praising <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for quick action on a $ 3.9 billion bill to provide emergency help to farmers whose crops and livestock are suffering because of this year's drought. `` The legislation that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is set to pass is excellent, far-reaching legislation that provides assistance to livestock and crop producers,'' the committee, chaired by <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON>, a Democrat, said in its resolution. A <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee approved a compromise version of the bill Thursday, and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved it Monday. The legislation was expected to receive final legislative approval in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> as early as Tuesday. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is expected to sign it into law within days of receiving it. Governors at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> annual meeting this week in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> has been particularly cooperative in aiding the drought relief effort. `` I've been in this business a long time, folks, and I've never seen this kind of response from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON>, a member of the governors' agriculture committee The committee approved the 67-page report from <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON>'s task force. The report urges federal and state governments to give continuing attention and support to rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as it fights to cope with depressed farm prices and declining value of farm land. The task force's report said the average price of farm land per acre went from $ 219 in 1972 to $ 823 in 1982, then back down to $ 547 in 1987. It urged states to help rural communities prepare for the future by creating special offices for rural affairs, providing tailored development information for rural areas and helping rural industries develop new products and find new markets. The report also urged <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to shape federal policies with more sensivitity to their impact on rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
