<HEAD>Iran Calls for Vigilance, But People Seem Ready for Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian leaders issued new calls for vigilance Monday, the day the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general announced a cease-fire in the long war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, but people in the Iranian capital seemed ready for peace. Newspapers carried reports on a Cabinet meeting in which members stressed the need `` for complete readiness and presence of combatants'' and more military volunteers. State television said the Iraqis shelled a village, wounding three civilians, and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported several violations of Iranian air space by <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> fighters. Residents of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> appeared convinced the end to the fighting was at hand. Even President <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, who expressed serious doubts about the truce prospects a few days ago, told an international conference the 8-year-old war `` is apparently coming to a close.'' He told a conference of Islamic scholars, however, that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s conduct during negotiations at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` gives us the right to have doubts about their real aims. <PERSON> Kayhan </PERSON>, one of the main afternoon papers, carried the headline `` Cease-fire to be announced tonight.'' Inside were photographs and brief biographies of `` martyrs'' _ Iranians killed in action. <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general, announced Monday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that the truce will begin Aug. 20 and peace negotiations between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> will open five days later in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. A driver who spoke English and said he formerly held a well-paid job in construction, told a 