<HEAD>Federal Safety Investigators Call For More Controller Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal safety investigators called Monday for a `` back-to-basics'' training program for air traffic controllers at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s busy O'Hare International Airport because of an unusually high number of controller errors. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said that a majority of the controller errors recorded at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>'s radar control facility during the first six months of the year involved a `` breakdown in basic -LRB- controller -RRB- skills.'' But the safety board said problems at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>, the second busiest airport in the world with an average of nearly 2,200 takeoffs and landings a day, go beyond controller skills. It called on the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to take immediate actions to provide controllers at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> with newer and better radar and computer equipment, find ways to increase controller staffing, reduce peak traffic loads, improve controller training and develop better quality assurance. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment directly on the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> recommendations, which came out of a special safety board investigation of <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>'s air traffic operations because of a sudden increase in controller errors earlier this year. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, however, announced that it planned a special broad-ranging review of <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> by a team of agency and aviation industry experts with a report to be submitted to <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> by Sept. 20. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said the review will go beyond air traffic control questions and include an examination of the airport's overal