<HEAD>With AM-Detroit Newspapers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Detroit Papers To Join 19 Others With Working Agreements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> will be among 20 cities in which two newspapers have combined some of their operations to keep one of the publications alive, according to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The joint operating agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and the Detroit News, approved Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, is the fifth approved under the Newspaper Preservation Act. The law, enacted in 1970, allows a limited antitrust exemption to preserve independent editorial voices in a community where one newspaper is in danger of failing. Many agreements that had joined the operations of newspapers in other cities before the law was enacted were grandfathered under the act and allowed to continue in effect, said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maguire </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ANPA </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president and general counsel. Those pre-1970 agreements had been reached by the newspapers themselves without need of any government action. Previous agreements approved under the Newspaper Preservation Act involved newspapers <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, in 1974; <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> in 1979; <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, in 1980 and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in 1982. The <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> agreement later was dissolved. According to <PERSON> Maguire </PERSON>, other joint operating agreements grandfathered under the act and still in effect involve newspapers in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn.