<HEAD>Two Afghan Airmen Defect To Pakistan in Fighter Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Afghan airmen in a Soviet-built MiG-19 abandoned a bombing mission over <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Monday and flew their fighter jet to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, where they asked for political asylum, authorities said. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> officials meanwhile refused to confirm or deny newspaper accounts that the <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> government was holding a Soviet pilot shot down last week. Authorities at the northwest border village of <LOCATION> Parachinar </LOCATION> said the two Afghan fliers landed their fully armed plane, handed over sidearms and asked for asylum. They said the men told <LOCATION> Parachinar </LOCATION> airport security that they, along with another two fighters, had been sent from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to bomb Moslem guerrilla positions in eastern <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION> province. While the others attacked <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION>, the pilot swerved his aircraft toward <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, they said. Airport security fired on the MiG, fearing it was coming in to bomb the airport although the pilot, identified as Maj. <PERSON> Munir </PERSON>, and the other airman, Capt. <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON>, advised the control tower they wanted to defect. They circled the airport four times before they were allowed to land, local authorities said. The fighter was loaded with rockets and bombs. Newspaper reports said a Soviet airman was flown to <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, the Pakistani capital, after surviving the downing of his Su-20 ground attack fighter by a U.S.-built <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> air force F-16 last Thursday. The plane reportedly was shot down near the border village of <LOCATION> Miranshah </LOCATION>. Over the course of the 10-year war in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, a half-dozen <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> pilots have defected to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> with their aircraft. This was the first defection reported since the Soviets began their withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15. Cross-border incursions in Pakistani airspace have occurred frequently during the long conflict between the Marxist government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and Islamic guerrillas. An air force official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said `` there has been some increase'' since the signing of an April 14 agreement providing for the phased withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Guerrilla reports from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Waziristan </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Miranshah </LOCATION> is located, said four Afghan refugees were killed last Wednesday when a Soviet or Afghan fighter jet bombed Pakistani territory.
