<HEAD>Low-Key UN Chief Having Success with Peace and Truce Accords</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> is mild of manner and would not boast of his diplomatic skill, but he had reason for pride Monday when he announced a cease-fire in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war. The Iran-Iraq war is the latest in several seemingly intractable conflicts for which the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has been asked to help find a solution. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is withdrawing its estimated 115,000 soldiers from a 10-year-old civil war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> under a U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14. Combatants in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> have asked the world organization to find ways of ending their wars without a defeat for any party. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s diplomatic successes in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the gulf contrast with his early disappointment in the 74-day <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> war between <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. It was fought in 1982, the year after he became <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief executive. The soft-spoken diplomat from <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, now 68, is known for discretion and diligence. He likes to quote the French aphorism `` Le ton fait la chanson,'' which means the melody makes the song, not a loud voice. The secretary-general tried to create harmony between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> as <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s fleet of warships steamed toward the Falklands, but both sides hardened their positions after two weeks of talks. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> also claims the islands, which it calls the Malvinas. Before the Falklands conflict ended, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The Israelis defied <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> demands for a cease-fire and withdrawal, and bypassed the 7,000-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. With infinite patience, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> insists it is `` much easier for a government to make concessions to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> than to make concessions to one another or to a big power.'' That theory bore fruit in the past week, when <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> abandoned its demand for direct talks with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as a first step toward peace, accepting <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s compromise suggestion for direct talks immediately after a cease-fire takes effect. He announced Monday that the truce would begin Aug. 20 and the peace talks Aug. 25. After he became secretary-general, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said he would not seek a second five-year term because the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief must remain independent and not curry favor with the five permanent <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members. He relented, however, and was re-elected in 1986 with no serious opposition. A career diplomat, he was <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> from 1971-75 and served on the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in 1973-74. He was <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> special representative to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in 1975-77 and, in 1979, was appointed undersecretary-general for political affairs. He held that post until becoming secretary-general and also was special representative to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1981.
