<HEAD>U.N. Chief Announces Date of Iran-Iraq Cease-fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with reaction,
other. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> announced Monday that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> will begin a cease-fire in their 8-year-old war on Aug. 20 and will open peace negotitions five days later in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. `` The restoration of peace will bring to the peoples of both countries victories far greater than those of war,'' he said in a statement, capping a full year of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peace efforts and three weeks of intense, delicate diplomacy. The <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war killed or wounded more than 1 million people and cost hundreds of billions of dollars. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief told the 15-nation <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> the two sides would begin direct talks on a comprehensive peace settlement Aug. 25 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. He said he would preside and the level of the talks was to be decided. `` I now call upon the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the Republic of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to observe a cease-fire and to discontinue all military action on land, at sea and in the air as of 0300 GMT on 20 August 1988,'' he said in his statement. The starting time of 3 a.m. <ORGANIZATION> Greenwich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> Aug. 20 is 11 p.m. EDT Aug. 19. `` I have been assured by the two parties to the conflict that they will observe this cease-fire in the context of the full implementation of Resolution 598,'' a peace plan adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> more than a year ago. As he spoke, the envoys of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> were both present in the Security Council for the first time since the war started. But Iranian Ambassador <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> and Iraqi Ambassador <PERSON> Ismat </PERSON> <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON> did not acknowledge each other's presence. The council will meet Tuesday to authorize a 350-man unarmed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peace-keeping force, including a naval contingent, to monitor the cease-fire and troop withdrawal. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> did not announce dates for all peace plan elements, including troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange, direct peace talks and an investigation into which side started the war. The agreement is the second <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> negotiating success this year. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> is withdrawing Soviet soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> under a U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14. `` This is not a personal success for me,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said later in answer to reporters' questions. `` It is a success for the two parties, for the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, for the U.N. organization.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON>, later told a news conference: `` I wish to declare my government is prepared to accept the demand of the secretary-general and that of the entire world community to refrain from any military action on land, sea and air, starting today.'' `` Let me express my sincere hope that today's historic announcement will be the first step in the implementation of all provisions of Resolution 598, and the achievement of a just, comprehensive and honorable setttlement, returning peace and stability to all the region.''. Asked if <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was ready to make peace with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, he said: `` Of course, there is no question about it.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON> told reporters: `` This is a happy day. I do n't think anyone is unhappy We in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been waiting for this day ... `` Now we begin the arduous but happy march that begins from here. I am sure it will not be a smooth road, but it will be much more pleasant than fighting and bloodshed.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> told reporters: `` This is a historic date for the participating countries, a historic day for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> which has pressed so hard to bring this war to and end, and a truly historic day for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had foreign exchange reserves of $ 35 billion when the war began and now owes an estimated $ 60 billion. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has not borrowed, but its foreign exchange reserves have declined to a few billion dollars. A financial journal published in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, estimates <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> needs $ 80 billion and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> $ 30 billion to rebuild transportation, oil installations, housing, factories, schools and hospitals. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> negotiations had been deadlocked over <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s demand for direct talks with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> before a cease-fire. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> had rejected that demand, saying it wanted a truce first, then direct talks. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> proposed a compromise formula that includes direct talks immediately after a cease-fire. People in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> seemed convinced Monday the fighting would end. A 25-year-old man named <PERSON> Fahrad </PERSON> said he was excused from military service because of injuries suffered in a car crash while studying petrochemical engineering in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. He told an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter: `` Many of my generation are dead. In a way I was lucky to have been in that accident.'' Diplomats in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> said efforts to keep the guns silent may continue for years because of border and other issues. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in September 1980 after border skirmishes. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said: `` We may finally see an end to that long and bloody war. ... I applaud and encourage the efforts of Secretary-General Perez de Cuellar.'' About two weeks will be needed to deploy the peacekeepers and their operation will cost $ 74 million for the six months authorized. They will be drawn from about 25 nations, each paying for the soldiers it sends. A report by <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iran-Iraq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> will: _ Establish agreed cease-fire lines on the basis of forward defended areas existing when the truce begins, with adjustments when the sides are too close _ Monitor compliance with the cease-fire _ Investigate alleged violations and restore the situation in each case _ Use negotiations to prevent changes in the status quo pending withdrawal to internationally recognized boundaries _ Supervise, verify and confirm withdrawal _ Obtain agreement on other arrangements, such as weapons limitations near the border and patrolling of sensitive areas by <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> naval personnel
