<SECOND>AM-Elephants,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>House OKs Bill To Combat Illegal Ivory Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Monday passed legislation to combat illegal trafficking in African elephant ivory. Sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by voice vote, the measure would prohibit imports into this country of any ivory taken in violation of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species. That worldwide agreement uses a system of quotas and ivory markings in an effort to regulate the international trade in ivory from African elephants, whose numbers have fallen to an estimated 700,000 from 1.5 million in 1979. The bill would ban importation of raw ivory from any nation without a native elephant population and would prohibit exportation of raw ivory from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The legislation would require the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to license all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial importers and exporters of ivory and to declare moratoria on ivory imports from nations lacking adequate elephant protection programs. The department would have to do a country-by-country review of the programs and decide by Dec. 31, 1989, whether a particular nation's preservation efforts are adequate. Violations of the proposed law would carry a maximum civil penalty of $ 5,000 and a maximum criminal penalty of a $ 200,000 fine and a year in prison.
