 <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON>, a professional soldier who became a major figure in the French Resistance during the Nazi occupation of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in World War II, died at the age of 82, family members said Monday. Frenay died Saturday in <LOCATION> Porte-Vecchio </LOCATION> on the French Mediterranean island of <LOCATION> Corsica </LOCATION>, the home of his wife, <PERSON> Chilina </PERSON>, and was buried there Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported. Cause of death was not given. His only child, <PERSON> Henri </PERSON>, said in a statement that a Mass would be celebrated in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> at a date to be announced later. On Monday night, the presidential palace said in a statement that President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> would attend the ceremony and `` would hope the nation renders a solemn homage to <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON>.'' Last March, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, himself a Resistance figure, awarded Frenay the Grand Cross of the Legion of Honor, calling him `` the incarnation of the young, interior Resistance.'' Frenay _ known by the pseudonym <PERSON> Charvet </PERSON> _ founded the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> during the occupation, the Resistance group Combat, and the underground <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> newspaper of the same name. Born Nov. 19, 1905 in <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON> was educated at <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s military academy, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cyr </LOCATION> A captain when <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in May 1940, <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON> was captured the following month, but escaped. He returned to <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> where he at once began organizing resistance against the Germans. After the Liberation, he served in the provisional governments of 1944 and 1945 as minister for prisoners, deportees and refugees. He was promoted to colonel in 1945. <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON> wrote several books on the Resistance, including `` La Nuit Finira'' -LRB- The Night Will End -RRB-, published in 1974; `` Volontaires de la Nuit'' -LRB- Volunteers of the Night -RRB- 1975, and `` L'Enigme Jean Moulin'' -LRB- The Jean Moulin Riddle -RRB- 1977. His vision of his mission differed from that of Gen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>, who wanted all resistance groups to work under the umbrella of his London-based leadership. `` Well, <PERSON> Charvet </PERSON>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> will choose between you and me,'' Frenay, quoting <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>, recounted in his book `` La Nuit Finira.'' In the 1965 presidential election, <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON> called for a vote against <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>, who he said represented a `` haughty and obsolete nationalism.'' After the war, <PERSON> Frenay </PERSON> became administrator of a toy company.
