ederal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said the ruling, for example, allows a state official to use contributions from corporations _ illegal for federal offices _ to cover some expenses connected with raising money for a congressional race. <PERSON> Wertheimer </PERSON> also criticized <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> and other members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for failing to produce `` a single piece of meaningful campaign finance reform legislation'' in recent years. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said, however, that the panel wo n't propose any major reform package until the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> first passes one. Senate Democrats ran into paralyzing Republican filibusters in 1987 and 1988 when they tried to move a bill setting up spending limits for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> races.
