convention opens. He made an unusual appearance for a nominee-to-be _ speaking in person to the platform committee about what he wants in the document to be adopted here next week. He dismissed the Democrats' platform, adopted last month in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, as a `` document of deceit.'' And he told the platform committee, `` We need to make this campaign a plan for the future, a statement of solutions, not an exercise in evasion. We should make our principles and our policies crystal clear to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people.'' He missed no opportunity to attack <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` He's the stealth candidate,'' the vice president said. `` For while he ca n't decide about the stealth bomber, he favors instead stealth policies _ they can be neither seen nor heard. ... His campaign jets from place to place, but no issues show up on the radar screen. `` Their nominee spoke for 50 minutes in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and failed to mention the most important issue of our time: how to make the world a safer place,'' he added. The stealth bomber is a supersecret craft designed to evade detection. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said he supports development of the bomber but would not commit to deploying the craft until he saw how well it would operate. Touring the Superdome where he will receive the party's nomination next week, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> denied that he was engaging in negative campaigning `` No, no ... very positive,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told reporters. But he did say, `` We've got to get these differences in focus,'' as he toured a large room where teen-agers were making signs for the convention. Then, refering to the Democratic convention _ where he was a frequent target _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` That was negative campaigning.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had a brown-bag lunch _ turkey sandwich and potato chips _ with the construction workers who are turning the giant football arena into a political hall. `` This is my life, man, and I tell you it's looking great,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said as he looked around the mostly empty building. Members of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Contests spent Monday trying to resolve challenges to as many as 39 of the 48 delegates from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won the primary there, but supporters of television evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> made a run at taking over the party machinery. Regardless who is seated, the delegates must vote for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation to prohibit political contributions for state and local campaigns from being used for a federal race _ a step critics say amounts to protection for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The measure goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on a voice vote.
