<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fireworks exploded in the night sky over <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> early Tuesday and jubilant Iraqis fired thousands of bullets into the air to celebrate `` the great victory'' over <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The celebration came after <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> announced in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Monday that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had agreed to a cease-fire in their eight-year-old war. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said the cease-fire would start Aug. 20 and peace negotiations would take place five days later. Shortly after midnight, government television called on Iraqis `` to celebrate the great victory achieved by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'' on `` the greatest day of all.'' It announced a tree-day period of celebration. The war has killed or wounded about 1 million people and cost both countries billions of dollars. Iraqis danced on pickup trucks and waved palm leaves from the windows of cars driving through <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> as tracer bullets and flares flashed overhead. `` The war is over. Victory for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>,'' said a man at the entrance to the <PERSON> Al-Rashid </PERSON> hotel as he looked up at the fireworks. `` The war is over, praise be to God,'' said a woman beside him. `` Here, take this'' a security man said, offering a reporter an automatic rifle. The guard then fired the rifle into the sky, laughing with other security men across the street who unleashed scores of rounds from a machine gun. Not all of the bullets went skyward. A car in the Al-Rashid parking lot had a bullet hole in the hood. Children scampered through the streets collecting cartridges.
