<HEAD>Historic Commission Given Option Of Moving O'Neill House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owners of a boarding house where <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> wrote his first plays agreed Monday to give preservationists a chance to save the building by moving it to another location. The owners wanted to raze the house, built around 1860, to make way for a summer home, but the state won a temporary injunction blocking the demolition. The agreement, which still must be formally presented to the court, `` gives everybody at least something of what they want,'' said state Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Russ </PERSON>, representing the state <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The owners gave the state until January to decide whether the 1 -LCB- - story building can be moved, and until March 1, 1989 to remove the building from its site on a sandy stretch of the <LOCATION> Thames </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in southeastern <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Moukawsher </PERSON>, attorney for the four owners, said the house is run-down and that it would have been too much of a burden to restore it. <PERSON> Moukawsher </PERSON> had argued that the house, built in Carpenter Gothic style, was only of minor historical significance and that its importance had been exaggerated. The <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> family's summer home, <ORGANIZATION> Monte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cristo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cottage </ORGANIZATION>, is located only a block away from the boarding house and is listed as a National Historic Landmark. The boarding house could not receive that designation because of its historical similarity to the cottage, <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said. <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> was convalescing from tuberculosis when he was taken on as a winter guest at the boarding house in 1913-14, while the rest of his family traveled on a theater tour. During that time, he produced four one-act plays that were incorporated into his first published work, `` Thirst and Other One Act Plays,'' and his first full-length play, `` Bread and Butter,'' said historic preservationists. While moving the house would strip it of some of its historical significance, it still would be the building where <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> began his career as a dramatist, <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said. <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, who died in 1953, won four Pulitzer Prizes for his plays and the Nobel Prize in literature. The agreement was reached on the same day a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> hearing was set on whether the injunction should remain in effect pending a trial. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> conceded that the state would not have been able to prevent the home's ultimate destruction if a trial had been held.
