<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Insider trading on stolen Business Week stock tip columns has alarmed the magazine's rivals, compelling some to review their own security and recheck back issues to make sure they have n't been victimized, too. `` We do n't take any pleasure in what happened to Business Week, but we're in the enviable position of bolting the barn door before the horse escapes, or at least checking the locks,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Belis </PERSON>, spokesman for Fortune, which has a biweekly circulation of 755,000. `` We're checking the locks.'' <PERSON> Belis </PERSON> said a spot check of Fortune's `` Companies to Watch'' column going back several months showed no unusual prepublication activity in any stocks mentioned. Senior editorial officials at Forbes and Money, two other widely read business magazines, also said they were reassessing protection of market-sensitive material in the aftermath of the scandal at Business Week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> will be allowed to merge their business and production operations because the smaller <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> was in danger of financial failure stemming from years of steady and apparently irreversible losses, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said Monday. In approving the application for a joint operating agreement, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> rejected the recommendation of a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> administrative law judge who said the two newspapers' pricing policies were unrealistic. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, however, said there was little prospect for the Free Press to return to profitability in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s highly competitive market. `` For me, the continuing and persistent operating losses suffered by the Free Press over the course of nearly a decade, with no prospect of unilaterally reversing that economic condition in the foreseeable future, describes a newspaper ` in danger of financial failure','' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said in his opinion. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> told reporters that the Free Press' losses were not manipulated but came `` from intense competition.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years after Love Canal was declared a national disaster area because buried chemicals were oozing to the surface, the largely abandoned neighborhood remains at the center of environmental debate. The former chemical dump that forced hundreds of families from their homes has been fenced off and surrounded with clay and plastic liners to prevent chemicals from leaking into groundwater. Corroding drums of chemicals have been separated and complex runoff monitoring and collection systems have been built. But even though the contamination has been largely contained and state officials have begun to talk about restoring the neighborhood to residential use, critics think Love Canal and hundreds of similar sites throughout the nation will remain potential disasters until a safe disposal method is found.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Novelist <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON>, who created joy of life with `` Zorba the Greek'' and a religious storm with `` The Last Temptation of Christ,'' remains popular in his native land 30 years after his death. His novels sell thousands of copies every year, mainly in Greek but also in English, French, German and Japanese. He is believed to be the most-read writer in modern Greek. `` We have a huge turnover in the half-dozen major <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> novels. ... In Greek he's mostly bought by young people, and then the tourists pick up the foreign language copies,'' said <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dokimakis </PERSON>. He owns a leading bookstore in <LOCATION> Heraklion </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>, the island where <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> was born. <PERSON> Dokimakis </PERSON> said the two most popular novels are `` Zorba,'' an exuberant portrayal set on <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> of a man with a huge zest for life, and `` Last Temptation,'' which presents <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> as a weak, unstable man who doubts his divinity and dreams of making love to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdalene </PERSON>, the reformed sinner.
