<HEAD>From Wisecracking Waitress to Series Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If not for a bunch of guys sitting around a bar in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> a few years ago, there would be no `` Roseanne'' on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> this coming season. Well, maybe it is n't world peace, but it has changed the life of comedian <PERSON> Roseanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> who will star as the wisecracking `` domestic goddess'' in the half-hour comedy that might just be <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s best bet for a new season hit. `` I was a cocktail waitress. My customers encouraged me to go down to this comedy club. I did n't know it was there. So I went down there and watched everybody,'' she said. A year later she had written five minutes' worth of material that led her to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> where was called from the secondary stage at The Comedy Store to main room and discovered by comedy producer <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlatter </PERSON>. The routine at the root of this frenzy of success was described by <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> for a group of television critics: `` I go, ` Hi, I'm a housewife, domestic goddess, then I tell jokes about my kids and then I tell jokes about my husband and then I get off.'' Her remarkable poise as a woman busting into a man's standup-comic world came from the `` back-and-forthing'' with the boys in the bar `` If those guys had n't laughed, I probably would n't be doin' this now. She is pressed on just what one-liners so impressed cocktail purchasers that they would encourage her to go pro. `` Most of it is so filthy, you could n't print it,'' she says. Well, OK. `` This guy goes, ` Do you know any married women that do n't want to get a divorce but want to have an affair with a married guy who'll treat'em real good and spend a lot of money on'em and make love a lot and all this stuff? And I go _ ` Yeah. Your wife.''' <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>'s hapless and seemingly worthless husband is the butt of many of her jokes, but in real life <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Pentland </PERSON> was an early supporter of her career, helping develop her material. He is a writer and likely sometime performer on the sitcom, scheduled to debut probably in November. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> -LRB- `` Raising Arizona'' -RRB- plays her TV husband. `` My real husband is like a lot more bizarre than my character husband,'' <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said. `` He's very funny. He's like the funniest person I ever knew my whole life, and he's very bizarre and he does n't have any respect for anything, and he's very much an anarchist.'' They met when she was living in a commune in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> and `` he had the only toilet in the county'' since he worked as the night manager at a motel. `` We were really hippy people.'' `` Me and him went to this club the first time I ever went down there. We sat there together and we were both like really appalled at what they were saying on stage and like what's happened to comedy?' All the `` pig jokes about women'' convinced the two of them that <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> should take on the comedy establishment and offer `` the other side.'' <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>'s humor is more than yocks. It has a political, working-class edge that will likely find its way into the sitcom. She does n't like the sitcom moms offered to the TV public so far. `` You're just a working stiff and this is your job. I wish people would stop thinking it was destiny and start thinking it's a job. `` You try to keep everything light and funny as you can because there's no other way to survive being a working-class person without any money.'' <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said she loves <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> because `` she's so real and she seems like your neighbor and somebody you'd like to know.'' But she says she was baffled by the popularity of the old `` I Love Lucy'' show. `` I like <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> but I hated that show, because she has to beg her husband for five bucks and he spanks her ... I never ever understood that even as a little girl.'' <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramden </PERSON> on `` The Honeymooners'' are her favorites, ``'cause you know they love each other and they're just picking at each other, which is kind of the thing I want on our show, rather than ` Married ... with Children' and that mean thing. I just want to like this nice lady that's funny and has this edge, which is how I see myself.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: FROM THE `` IT'S A JOKE'' FILE _ <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> is still steamed about the potshots that <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> has taken at him since the megaphone incident a couple of years ago. At a recent news conference, <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> even impuned <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON>'s masculinity for not doing the `` guys'' thing and calling up and apologizing. `` I do n't expect <PERSON> David </PERSON> to do a mea culpa on the air But I would have thought he'd be enough of a man to pick up the phone and say, ` It's gotten out of hand, I'm sorry.' That has n't happened. I'm not asking for it to happen. I'm really not. I guess what I'm saying is the fact that it has n't happened tells me a lot about the guy.'' In an interview last year, <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> suggested forming a support group to meet in a church basement to help <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> get over his distress. The feud stems from the `` Today'' show's prime-time special in 1986 when <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> shouted out his window with a megaphone as `` Today'' was taping. <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> thought it was unprofessional. <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> maintains he was invited by the show's producer to pull such a prank, but someone apparently did n't warn <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
