 EDITOR'S NOTE _ <PERSON> Cloyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> is a pack rat. He's also a handyman, storekeeper, cobbler, mechanic, storyteller, artist, husband and father. In addition to running a cluttered general store in rural <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, he has spent half a century collecting derelict automobiles and other castoff items most people would call junk.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You wo n't find <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, on any map. But you wo n't come across many in these parts who do n't know of <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> and its `` founder,'' <PERSON> Cloyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>. `` I guess everyone knows about me,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> says, hands thrust in the pockets of his worn overalls. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> is proprietor of a ramshackle general store on a dirt road 7 miles north of <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>. A sign outside reads: <PERSON> WEBSTER </PERSON> MICHIGAN OPEN 7. TO 10 P.M. CLOSED SUNDAYS He has no post office in his store, but he's so well-known locally that mail addressed to <LOCATION> Webster </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, reaches him. Since first setting up shop here in 1932, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> has been collecting derelict automobiles and gadgets, pop bottles and hubcaps, batteries and milk jugs, toasters and sewing machines, all kinds of litter that together comprise something of a scrapbook of the 20th century. Indeed, a trip to <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> throws the visitor into a time warp, back to the days of <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> thermometers and 5-cent soda pop. <PERSON> Cloyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, a youthful-looking 70-year-old pack rat, storekeeper, cobbler, mechanic, storyteller, artist, husband and father. Surrounded by dairy farms that dot the rolling hills of west-central <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, some might call <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>'s 27 acres a junkyard. But among the rusting hulks of 1930s and'40s automobiles are some treasures. `` Sure, I know some of these things are worth a lot,'' he says. `` And I sell some of'em.'' He rummages through a box full of antique bottles. `` Here's one of them old Dr Pepper bottles. Betcha never seen one of them before.'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> will sell you anything you want. But if you ca n't pay, he's been known to make a deal. Cut him some wood, and he'll fix a battery free of charge. Batteries are his specialty. But, he says, he can fix just about anything `` if I can get the part.'' Chances are, he has it already. Even more remarkably, he knows where it is. `` Inventory? I keep it all up here,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> says, pointing to his soiled, green cap. Indeed, there is a touch of organization amid the apparent chaos. `` See that'36 <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>?'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> asks, pointing to the moss-covered automobile partially imbedded in the ground outside the back of his shop. `` It's filled with table-model radios. That'35 Chevy over there? Filled with gaskets. Only gaskets.'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> bought most of the old cars and bicycles, although some were abandoned after being dropped off for repairs. `` I used to buy everything that came along,'' he says. All are for sale. `` I can make any one of'em run,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> insists. Entangled in vines and weeds, are probably 500 bicycles and cars, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> estimates, not including all the ones in hundreds of pieces. About 2 -LCB- tons of hubcaps are piled up, reaching the branches of the trees. `` I'd clean it all out, but even if I took 10 tons a day out it would still take seven or eight years to get rid of it all,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> says. Inside the weathered building is a cluttered maze of spare parts and cases of soda bottles stacked to the ceiling, dark and narrow aisles leading to several rooms. There's a grocery section and a shoe repair section, where <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> uses car tires to make rubber soles _ `` guaranteed not to wear out.'' `` This is where I do my painting,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> says, indicating a cramped area by a window. There are enamel paints on a cluttered, flat surface, but no room to sit down. It is here that <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> gets away from it all, painting wildlife scenes on aluminum printing plates. `` Ten dollars apiece. I sell lots of'em,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> says, pointing to the hundreds of finished products piled in his `` art department.'' His subjects come from postcards, photographs, other paintings or from memory. `` I start about 30 of'em at a time,'' he says proudly, displaying his favorite nature scenes. `` I started drawing on little scraps of paper when I was in the Air Force so I'd remember what everything looked like,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> says, taking out a pile of the aging pencil drawings on a shelf. An 11th-grade dropout, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> spent four years in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, from 1942 to'46, closing the shop while he was gone. When he returned, he married, and he and his wife, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>, have been running the store ever since, living in a rickety house next door. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>'s 94-year-old father, a former farmer, lives down the road. The Websters have three grown children, one of whom lives nearby and sometimes helps out at the store, and eight grandchildren. Asked if any of his children might take over the business after he retires, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> hesitates, as though it was the first time he's thought about it `` I do n't know,'' he says. `` But I'm not retiring any time soon.'' That's good news to his regulars. `` I've been a regular for five or six years,'' says customer <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Christner </PERSON>, who was here this time for a battery part. `` Whenever I get a flat tire, <PERSON> Cloyce </PERSON> always fixes them _ he fixes everything.'' And though some days are slower than others, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> insists he does a hearty business, especially considering he does n't own a telephone. `` If someone wants something, they'd better see me directly,'' he says. On Sundays, shaven and spruced up, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> closes shop and heads for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hesperia </ORGANIZATION>, where he sings in the choir. `` I think I'm pretty good,'' he says, smiling, exposing his two teeth _ both on the bottom.
</TEXT>
