<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> took on a Broadway musical right after he went into a prime-time television series, with the understanding that it would be goodbye <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> if the TV show turned into a hit. Instead, `` <ORGANIZATION> Eisenhower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON>'' was canceled by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and `` Romance Romance,'' a modest little musical that uses only four actors and minimal scenery, has blossomed on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. `` The timing was incredible,'' <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> said the other day, sitting in his dressing room at the <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> Theater. `` We wrapped the series in mid-February and started rehearsals for ` Romance Romance' in March. `` I came into it saying, ` I've got a TV series and may have to go back in mid-June,''' he recalls. `` And the producers said, ` OK.''' `` Romance Romance,'' two separate one-act musicals, looks at love in two very different places: turn-of-the-century <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> and trendy, modern-day <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> plays a rakish man about town in the first act and an anguished yuppie contemplating an affair with a friend's wife in the second. The show and <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> were nominated for 1988 Tony awards. Neither won, but the musical received national exposure on the Tony telecast and has found a growing audience. A recording by <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> Classics is scheduled for release in late summer. For <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON>, the recognition secured a stage reputation that sprouted before he first went off to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to do television. The 33-year-old <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> is one of those actors who looks at ease in both mediums, although he says he is more comfortable on stage than on television. `` I find the camera to be confining, but I've gotten over that,'' he says. `` I tend to like to be physical on stage _ to move and to do things.'' Television requires a certain precision, he says _ hitting your mark and then being still. `` How can you act?'' <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> asks. `` But that's the trick of it when you're coming from the theater. Now I'm used to it.'' <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON>, who hails from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, found performing a part of his life while growing up. `` I always sang and that led to doing theater,'' he says. He went to the Univerity of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> to study business but later switched to theater. `` I left school and came here to work in 1976, not study theater,'' <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> recalls. `` But I ended up studying my head off all over town for years.'' Still, <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> had a job in show business the third day he was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, although he had to leave town again to get it. The work was in a dinner theater in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> which was doing `` Shenandoah,'' a musical that supported him a lot during his first years in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Whenever times got lean, it seemed like a company of <ORGANIZATION> ` </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shenandoah </ORGANIZATION>' would come up,'' he says. The actor finally made it to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> in 1983, seven years after arriving in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He survived `` Marilyn: an American Fable,'' a short-lived and much-maligned musical based on the life of <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>. In it, he played <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION