<HEAD>North Korea _ A Stark Contrast To The South</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spotlight-South Korea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Part of a three-story package</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has developed into one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s success stories, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is one of the world's most engimatic nations The north, occupying the top half of the 600-mile long peninsula, is feared for its often wild, irrational policies and its willingness to use violence against its opponents. North Korean President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>, now 76, rules with a monolithic personality cult that teaches <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> to idolize him. Giant statues of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, called `` Great Leader,'' dot the country, the state-run media are filled with slavish praise of the president and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> are taught that he is loved around the world. North Koreans generally wear badges bearing <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s picture. `` The centralized control which demands total loyalty to the leader has produced a pervasive and almost suffocating cult of personality,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said in a recent report. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> is attempting to build the world's first communist dynasty; his son, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jung </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, has been designated to succeed him. A personality cult is also being built around the son, who is called `` Dear Leader.'' The ruling <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> enforces rigid control over all aspects of life. Independent political groups or other organizations are not tolerated, religion is outlawed and dissent or opposition is suppressed. But the north faces mounting problems. Chronic mismanagement, rigid state planning and massive military spending have crippled the economy and there are reports of food shortages. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1987 because the first nation ever to be declared in default on its foreign loans by international banks. North Korean diplomats have been caught selling drugs, liquor and watches in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in desperate schemes to raise hard currency. The north invaded the south in 1950 to trigger the bloody Korean War. It maintains the world's sixth largest army and has repeatedly carried out terrorist attacks against the south. The north was blamed for the bombing of a <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> commercial airliner that crashed near <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> last Nov. 29, killing 115 people. The North Koreans deny any involvement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14, and Thereafter.</NOTE>
