<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Vibes''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Raiders of the Lost Ark,'' the <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> @ <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> homage to the Saturday matinee serial, spawned a host of films in the same genre, ranging from the good -LRB- `` Romancing the Stone'' -RRB- to the poor -LRB- `` The Golden Child'' -RRB-. Now comes `` Vibes,'' which lands somewhere in between. The new <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> release most resembles `` Romancing the Stone'' in that an antagonistic couple are thrown into a fortune quest in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> wilderness, falling in love along the way. `` Vibes'' has some other attributes as well, including stunning Ecuadorian scenery and the movie debut of rock superstar <PERSON> Cyndi </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauper </PERSON>. The story begins promisingly in a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> psychic lab operated by <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sands </PERSON> -LRB- `` Room with a View'' -RRB-. Among his subjects is <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldblum </PERSON>, a museum worker who can reveal people's secrets by touching their personal possessions, and Miss <PERSON> Lauper </PERSON>, a blond bimbo who can foretell the future with the help of a spirit companion named <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON>. The pair take an instant dislike for each other, and their feelings intensify when they arrive in <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>. What are they doing in <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>? Well, it seems that a shady character resembling the TV detective <PERSON> Columbo </PERSON> has enlisted them to help find his lost son. Why they would trust such a person is one of the many mysteries contained in the script. Expectably, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON>'s ruse is exposed. What he is really after is Incan treasure hidden for centuries in the Andes. The search has already claimed two lives, but the lure of fortune has still attracted thugs and adventurers who will use any means to snatch it first. Such goings-on provide a reasonable basis for a high-tech, action-adventure. So what goes wrong? For one thing, the leading characters sound like vintage <PERSON> Damon </PERSON> <PERSON> Runyon </PERSON>, and the script writers, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Babaloo </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandel </PERSON>, have supplied one-liners that only now and then zing. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwapis </PERSON> directed with a good eye for action, but his actors seldom shine. <PERSON> Goldblum </PERSON>, who has created a number of memorable characters, is strangely restrained. <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> veers from the amusing to the annoying. That brings us to the celebrated Miss <PERSON> Lauper </PERSON>. She is typecast as the wise-cracking babe in search of a man, and her role seems to duplicate <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> in `` Born Yesterday.'' Yet there are no false notes in the singer's portrayal, and at times she can be quite touching. A film career could be assured if _ a big if _ she can slip into roles that depart from her music videos. <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Blum </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganz </PERSON> produced `` Vibes,'' which is rated PG for language and excitement. Running time: 99 minutes.
