 `` Walker'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> Home Video; VHS @ Beta, $ 79.95; Rated R -RRB- `` <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>,'' based on a true story about an early American incursion into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, is one of those movies that flopped at the box-office but sounds as if it might be an unappreciated gem just waiting to be rediscovered on ideo. Unfortunately, even on the home screen, `` Walker'' is still a flop _ though with its timely subject it can hardly fail to generate some interest. The film, directed by <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, retells the story of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a soldier of fortune who led a bloody invasion of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in the 1850s. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, as portrayed by <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, is a ruthless idealist, who as he orders mass slaughters of civilians, mouths platitudes about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s duty to `` protect our neighbors from oppression'' _ and apparently believes what he's saying. According to the filmmakers, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> sets out on his expedition at the urging of <ORGANIZATION> Cornelius </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION>, played here by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> as a flatulent, foul-mouthed old tyrant who wants to protect his railroad line running through <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> from rival nationalist groups. The climax of the film is an impassioned speech <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> gives _ shortly before his one-man rule is toppled and he is executed _ in which he tells the <LOCATION> Nicaraguan </LOCATION> people that `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will never leave you alone.'' Chilling words, but <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> runs the contemporary angle into the ground by littering the movie with deliberate anachronisms like helicopters, cigarette machines and personal computers. Much of the dialogue and direction seems sloppy and confused, and there has n't been so much blood spilled on screen since `` The Wild Bunch.'' Oscar-winner <PERSON> Marlee </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlin </PERSON> has about five good minutes early on as <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s deaf girlfriend. But once she dies of cholera, both he and the movie go downhill fast. _ By <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
