 `` The Lost Weekend,'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>; VHS @ Beta, $ 59.95; Not rated -RRB- It is fascinating and frightening to watch <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Milland </PERSON> as the literate, desperate alcoholic <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Birnam </PERSON> in `` The Lost Weekend.'' His performance earned him an Academy Award in <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s 1945 movie, which also was named best picture. <PERSON> Milland </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyman </PERSON> are the film's stars, but alcohol is the main character. Taken from the <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> novel of the same name, `` The Lost Weekend'' shows three days in <LOCATION> Birnam </LOCATION>'s life _ horrible drunken days when <PERSON> Birnam </PERSON> sinks to the depths of his soul, tormented by his failure as a writer. He rummages madly through his brother's apartment in search of a bottle of whiskey he himself hid but lost, trudges relentlessly through <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> in search of an open shop to pawn his typewriter. In one of the film's saddest moments, he chooses a sip from his tumbler of liquor over the kiss of <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Wyman </PERSON> -RRB-, who loves him. Still, <PERSON> Birnam </PERSON>, who talks of writing a novel called `` The Bottle,'' is witty and eloquent. Drink, he tells a bartender, may shrink his liver and pickle his kidney. `` But what does it do to my mind? It tosses the sandbags overboard so the balloon can soar.'' It makes no difference that the movie is 43 years old, or that it's in black and white _ even today there could be no more persuasive advertisement against alcohol abuse. _ By <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> MacVean </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
