<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--BearResearch Adv11   08-08 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Bear Research, Adv 11,0557</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 11, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pen-Raised Bears Released To Test Survival Skills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEANNE WAXMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mama bear is a crowd-pleaser, especially with a roly-poly cub romping at her side. But what's a zoo to do when baby grows up? Too often, surplus pen-reared black bears are sold, traded to dubious buyers or killed, and the mother bred again so zoo visitors wo n't be robbed of the baby bear experience, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON>, a wildlife science professor. <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> are tracking radio-collared bears released from zoo areas into the <ORGANIZATION> Cherokee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. Pen-raised black bears have been used in research in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, but `` this is the first time we've made a concerted effort to keep track of them,'' <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON> said. `` We want to learn more about how they react to a new environment after having been born in captivity ...'' `` The main thrust of the study is to determine simply if these animals will make it in the wild and if they're suitable for release,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. `` That's the big question. Should we even take these bears off the hands of zoos, or should we just allow them to be bought and sold?'' Six bears, wearing radio collars, have been released, three each from the Ober <LOCATION> Gatlinburg </LOCATION> and Grandfather Mountain resort zoos. One bear grew dependent on area residents for ice cream and other food handouts. When the zoo that had housed it declined to take it back, the bear had to be killed. The resort later relented and took back another bear after similar problems arose, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. A third bear was found dead in the forest. Foul play is suspected and an autopsy is pending. Radio contact has been lost with a fourth bear. Despite the problems, neither <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> is ready to give up. About 20 pen-raised black bears have been released into the wild in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> over the last 10 to 15 years, but without radio collars there's no way of knowing their whereabouts, <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON> said. In the past, tattoos and ear tags were used on pen-raised bears. At least three have turned up dead as the result of legal hunts, which tells researchers they managed to adapt, at least to nature. The handling of bears in captivity has a lot to do with their odds of making it in the wild, <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON> said. Often, they're fed dried dog food rather than berries and acorns, and are given treats by zoo visitors. Neither practice boosts their chances of adapting. In addition, their cages are sometimes bereft of places to climb and hide, a more natural environment, and they're allowed too much contact with humans. Several years ago, the state prohibited the caging of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> black bears in areas other than bona fide zoos or zoological parks. The law does n't require special diets or cages to help the bears survive in the wild if the need arose. `` My hope is that the state game people say to the people who generate these animals, ` We need to do a, b, c and d. Otherwise, we ca n't work with you,''' <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 11</NOTE>
