<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mama bear is a crowd-pleaser, especially with a roly-poly cub romping at her side. But what's a zoo to do when baby grows up? Too often, surplus pen-reared black bears are sold, traded to dubious buyers or killed, and the mother bred again so zoo visitors wo n't be robbed of the baby bear experience, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON>, a wildlife science professor. <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> are tracking radio-collared bears released from zoo areas into the <ORGANIZATION> Cherokee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. `` The main thrust of the study is to determine simply if these animals will make it in the wild and if they're suitable for release,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. `` That's the big question. Should we even take these bears off the hands of zoos, or should we just allow them to be bought and sold?'' Six bears, wearing radio collars, have been released, three each from two resort zoos. One grew too dependent on people for food handouts. When the zoo declined to take it back, the bear had to be killed. The resort later took back another bear. A third was found dead and radio contact was lost with a fourth. The handling of bears in captivity has a lot to do with their odds of making it in the wild, <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON> said. Often, they're fed dried dog food rather than berries and acorns, and are given treats by zoo visitors. Neither practice boosts their chances of adapting. In addition, their cages are sometimes bereft of places to climb and hide, a more natural environment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 11</NOTE>
