<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv11   08-08 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 11,0632</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 11, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Algae Could Lead to Agricultural Economies In Arid Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Algae growing in ponds in the Israeli desert could lead to new products to bring agriculture to arid regions. `` We are seeding plants that would never grow in the desert,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> botanist <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramus </PERSON>. `` This project is in its infancy. What we are developing now will come to fruition in the year 2000 and later.'' <PERSON> Ramus </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gurion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researchers are growing algae in labs and transferring them to ponds in the Valley of Arava in the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION>. The ponds, fed by fossil water from 3,000-foot wells, each hold a different type of algae. They also are growing Saint <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> fish in the ponds. The fish produce nitrogen to help the algae grow and bring a good price at market. `` Aquaculture of Saint <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> fish is becoming a big industry there. It's a real delicacy for them,'' <PERSON> Ramus </PERSON> said. `` One fish is enough for a meal. It's like the catfish or crawfish industry in the Southeast.'' The algae can be used to produce beta carotene, a source of Vitamin A; phycolloids, which are food thickeners; and biliproteins, which can be used in food colorings, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Marsh Grass Research Aimed At Preventing Coastal Erosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN MEADOW, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers in this small town are watching the grass grow _ and hoping to protect coastal wetlands from wind, waves and development that erode thousands of acres a year. The grass grown on 11 acres of ponds are n't protected from disease or weather, they're not fertilized and the only thing out of the ordinary they get is a daily dose of saltwater, from pumps that simulate the tide. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Soil Conservations Service researchers hope the smooth cut-grass, giant cut-grass and gulf cord grass will prevent the coastal erosion that takes some 32,000 acres a year of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s 3.2 million acres of coastal wetlands A tough, reedy carpet of such marsh grass can form a natural barrier against tides, waves, wind and the effects of dredging canals and exploring for oil while the roots hold the soil in place, said the agency's <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutshall </PERSON>. The project began in 1984 on land owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an oil and gas company, and researchers expect to know within a year what types are promising and within five years those that are suitable for seed production and aerial seeding projects. `` We've learned an awful lot with these plants,'' <PERSON> Cutshall </PERSON> said. `` There was virtually no information on how gulf cord grass grows, so we've done some original work there. And we've done some original work on smooth cut-grass.'' What remains, he said, `` is to find a plant that has the best of everything.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Heating Young Chickens Can Make Them Heat-Resistant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chickens die during heat waves because they ca n't sweat, but heating chicks seems to make them more resistant as adults, says a researcher who does n't have `` the foggiest idea'' why. Chickens exposed to 95 to 100 degree temperatures when they are 5 days old, and again when they are 6 weeks old, seem to have a survival rate 70 percent to 95 percent better than unheated chickens, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Denbow </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> associate professor of poultry science. `` It's kind of neat.'' Asked how it works, he said, `` We do n't have the foggiest idea.'' Chickens cool off by panting, which evaporates water through their respiratory systems, said <PERSON> Denbow </PERSON>, who has spent three years testing the birds. Broilers are usually ready for market at about six to seven weeks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End of Adv05</HEAD>
