<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--HomeFurnishings:Trends     08-08 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home Furnishings: Trends,0857</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME FURNISHINGS: Trends</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY711</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After last year's record growth, furniture industry analysts projected business would flatten out in 1988. So far, their projections are on the mark. But that does n't mean the furniture manufacturers, many of them in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, are sitting on their hands. Faced with the industry's first prolonged no-growth period since 1982, the manufacturers are developing innovative ways to attract retailers and consumers. Some are pushing new furniture lines to catch the eyes of potential customers. Others are working to improve services. Prices have been sharpened and new marketing strategies devised. `` The people who will be successful will do their homework, come out with some new lines and sharpen their pricing,'' said High Point designer <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Culler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Culler </PERSON>, who designs furniture for 10 different companies, feels it will take good business acumen rather than exotic designs if manufacturers are to entice consumers to buy as they did in 1987. `` I've always said 80 percent of what we do is merchandising and 20 percent -LRB- is -RRB- design,'' he said in an interview. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPaolo </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in High Point, said the business slowdown during the first few months of this year caused some difficulties for some factories. `` Their cash flow has become squeezed,'' he said in an interview. `` We might start seeing some shorter work weeks.'' <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Reddan </PERSON>, an economist for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said shipments and orders from factories to retailers have been flat this year, when compared with the record levels of a year ago. First quarter shipments, measured by units, were up less than 1 percent over the same period in 1987, he said. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON>, a furniture industry analyst with Wheat, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, brokerage house, said the reductions could lead to shorter work weeks and smaller backlogs in orders. `` It's not that business is not clipping along at a good rate,'' he said. `` Retailers are not ordering as far in advance because the backlogs are n't as large. Business in the popular price points has been tough most of the year. But it's more complicated than to just say consumers are n't buying furniture.'' <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON> said many furniture retailers have been struggling to comply with the federal tax reforms of 1986. No longer can they pay their taxes on an installment basis and defer some payments, he said. `` Now they have to pre-pay the government before taking out of their inventories,'' he said. `` They are less generous in credit terms and stricter in inventories. `` We've seen a year of significant inventory liquidation,'' <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reddan </PERSON> stressed that 1987 was a record year for shipments and orders. `` You must remember that employment is at an all-time high in the furniture industry,'' he said. `` Flat is very good _ a lot better than some people had feared.'' Until last October's stock market crash, optimism was strong in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, the nation's leading producer of household goods. In 1987, manufacturers shipped nearly $ 15.8 billion worth of furniture, a 10 percent increase over 1986. Retail sales last year advanced 5 percent to $ 27.2 billion. Topping those figures is difficult when the growth in the national economy has slowed, especially when new home starts, housing resales and interest rates also reflect a slowdown over 1987. `` It will be a flat year at retail, down between 3 to 5 percent below last year in unit terms,'' <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON> said. Prior to last April's <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> in High Point, some analysts were predicting that manufacturers would bring out many new product lines to generate business. <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON> said that did n't turn out to be the case. `` If anything, many factories are cutting back on the number of items they offer,'' he said. `` When you produce 600 sofas at one time, the cost is less.'' Many manufacturers are working to strengthen their relationship with a smaller number of retailers by providing better services _ such as accelerated delivery, guaranteed delivery or better credit terms, <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Barentine </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Factories </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION>, said prospects are picking up for the fall furniture market. `` If interest rates remain stable as well as housing starts, and consumer demand is strong, we'll be OK,'' he said. <PERSON> Barentine </PERSON> said many manufacturers have decided to stay with successful lines rather than try to push new ones. They also follow consumer preference _ for example, in case goods. `` They're willing to pay and in return they demand high quality,'' Barentine said. <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON>, of Furniture Today, a trade publication based in High Point, said she does n't anticipate that manufacturers will respond to sluggish sales by introducing more new lines of furniture than they usually do at the twice-yearly markets in High Point. `` I do n't think we can say across the board there will be a lot of innovation in order to boost sales,'' she said.
</TEXT>
