<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home Furnishings: With Trends-Marketing,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME FURNISHINGS: With Trends-Marketing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One controversial furniture industry marketing tool has become the focus of a lawsuit filed by 13 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> retailers against <ORGANIZATION> Thomasville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, which implemented a policy in April restricting catalog and telephone sales. To continue as dealers of <LOCATION> Thomasville </LOCATION>'s high-end products, <LOCATION> Thomasville </LOCATION> said, its 51 retailers in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> must install a gallery. Like other manufacturers, <LOCATION> Thomasville </LOCATION> started a gallery program in 1982 in which its furniture is displayed in a room-like setting. `` It's a period of adjustment,'' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON>, of Furniture Today, a trade publication. `` The gallery alignment is a challenge facing the industry. It creates a strong relationship between the manufacturer and the retailer.'' Ms. <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON> said many smaller stores are reluctant to devote valuable floor space to one manufacture's furniture. The result is fewer dealers selling the products, she said. In <LOCATION> Thomasville </LOCATION>'s case, it was a profitable move. In 1982, <LOCATION> Thomasville </LOCATION> reported sales of $ 130 million through 4,000 retailers. Last year, the number of dealers stood at 555 _ with sales at $ 260 million. However, the 13 plaintiffs allege that restrictions on telephone and catalog sales violate antitrust laws. The 13 are among 40 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> retailers that have signed up for the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
