<HEAD>HOME FURNISHINGS: Bargains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Furniture bargains are out there, somewhere, says a prominent furniture restorer _ `` They're just hiding where you'd least expect to find them.'' One way to find them, says <PERSON> Homer </PERSON> <PERSON> Formby </PERSON>, is to run an ad in the local newspaper announcing, `` I Buy Used Furniture.'' It's better to say `` used'' furniture rather than `` antique,'' he says, to keep prices reasonable. Then make appointments with callers and go out on weekend `` treasure hunts.'' `` You'd be surprised at the number of people who have $ 20,000 worth of old furniture stuck in a dusty attic or musty basement,'' says <PERSON> Formby </PERSON>. Other places to look: `` Flea markets, junk shops and auctions... real estate sales and garage sales Often, people have lived with this furniture all their lives, and they're eager to get rid of it. `` Take your time looking, and be thorough. Look in all the nooks and crannies _ even behind doors.'' <PERSON> Formby </PERSON> says furniture does n't have to be 100 years old to be worth restoring. `` I've come across a lot of 50 - and 60-year-old reproductions worth as much, or more, than some 100-year-old antiques,'' he says `` So think twice before passing over any piece that's made of solid wood.''
