<HEAD>Dollar Higher in Europe, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was higher in late-morning European trading today, though dealers said its rise had been temporarily halted by West German central bank intervention. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> started selling dollars for West German marks early in the session to stem the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's rise and dealers said the market was not fazed initially. But by late morning, the intervention had at least temporarily halted the dollar's advance. `` It has put the dollar under control,'' said one trader in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. The dollar was boosted late Friday by good <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employment data for July, which fueled market speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will raise interest rates soon. Higher interest rates make the dollar a more attractive investment. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.85 Japanese yen to a closing 133.97. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted slightly lower at 133.93 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.9004 West German marks, up from 1.8890; 1.5887 Swiss francs, up from 1.5757; 6.4085 French francs, up from 6.3675; 2.14575 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1315; 1,400.75 Italian lire, up from 1,393.00; 1.2078 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2050 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6915 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6977 late Friday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 431.60 a troy ounce and at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 431.85. Both prices were down from Friday's late bid of $ 432.10 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 431.90, down from $ 433.00 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 434.00, up a penny from Saturday's $ 433.99. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.80 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $ 6.89.
