<SECOND>PM-Condoms-Women,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>To Maintain Growth, Condom Companies Targeting Women Buyers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New for PMs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE FALLS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The condom market is leveling off after heavy growth spurred by fear of AIDS, and the nation's two biggest manufacturers hope to maintain consumer interest by targeting female buyers, according to industry officials. <ORGANIZATION> Carter-Wallace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Schmid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> plan soon to release products in feminine-style packaging that they hope will encourage more women to buy the prophylactics. Women account for an estimated 40 percent of condom purchases, industry experts say. <ORGANIZATION> Schmid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-biggest condom seller with 35 percent of the market, wants to shore up declining sales by appealing to them Last month, the company laid off 150 temporary workers at its <LOCATION> Anderson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, manufacturing plant because of a drop in demand. One reason for the slower sales was the higher prices condom manufacturers recently began paying for <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> latex used to make most of the products. Officials also say new regulations by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> have trimmed profit margins by mandating a tenfold increase in condom testing. <PERSON> Schmid </PERSON> president <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> said sales remain strong, but are not near the lofty numbers that followed Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>'s advice last year to use condoms to avoid transmitting acquired immune deficiency syndrome. `` People realized the initial impact was not going to continue forever,'' <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> said of the sales surge. `` But we are at a higher production level now than pre-AIDS.'' <ORGANIZATION> Diana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> analyst who follows <ORGANIZATION> Carter-Wallace </ORGANIZATION>, says women can be important to the market if more begin relying on condoms for contraception, as recent studies show they are. `` I think -LRB- sales -RRB- are moderating,'' Ms. <PERSON> Temple </PERSON> said. `` People appear to be buying them. The key is if they are using them.'' Condom company officials would not estimate the dollar amount of their sales but said the industry estimates it will sell about $ 404 million worth of condoms in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year, which Ms. <PERSON> Temple </PERSON> said would represent a 20 percent rise in sales. To maintain consumer interest, <ORGANIZATION> Carter-Wallace </ORGANIZATION>, which controls half of the market, soon will be marketing <ORGANIZATION> Trojans </ORGANIZATION> for Women, spokeswoman <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Stecher </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Schmid </PERSON> soon will introduce <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> for Her and She's Sheik condoms, variations on two of the company's top-selling lines. Among the added feminine touches in the new products are a carrying case for each condom and disposable envelopes. `` The emphasis now is on educating young people to use condoms if they are sexually active and non-monogomous. We think young women are more likely to respond to this than young men,'' <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
