<FIRST>r f PM-RFD-TV     08-08 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RFD-TV,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>RFD-TV Hopes For Good Harvest of Viewers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rock' n' rollers have <ORGANIZATION> MTV </ORGANIZATION>, sports fans have <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> and investors have the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. Now, there's RFD-TV for farmers _ an idea its developers hope will reap a bountiful harvest of profits `` We're a whole new concept and we're delivering stories that no one else is delivering,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the satellite network scheduled to go on the air Aug. 15. `` It seems like there's always something going on with agriculture,'' he said. `` But one problem is farmers are not getting accurate or timely information on a daily basis or even an hourly basis.'' RFD-TV hopes to change that with 24-hour, seven-day a week programming available to households with a satellite dish, <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said in a recent interview, as workers scrambled to build sets and uncrate equipment in time for the network premiere. He said plans call for RFD-TV, named after the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service's old acronym for rural free delivery, to grow like the crops that will be its subject matter, expanding to cable and low-power television systems. <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON>, who was raised on a farm near <LOCATION> Elkhorn </LOCATION> and later worked as a commodity broker and satellite dish dealer, said he came up with the idea for RFD-TV about three years ago. There are 2.8 million home satellite dishes in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 250,000 in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. About 60 percent are in rural areas, <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. `` It's just a common sense project,'' he said. `` If you take a drive in the country you see a lot of dishes and they're going to be watching us.'' The programming wo n't be reruns of `` Hee-Haw,'' `` The Real McCoys'' or `` <LOCATION> Mayberry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> R.F.D. </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. He described the network as a cross between the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, but geared toward rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Universities in all 50 states will produce shows for RFD-TV and a live prime-time interview show in which viewers may phone in questions is planned. RFD-TV also will have its own barnyard take-off on home shopping _ video livestock auctions to give farmers a chance to expand their herds without leaving their living rooms, <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. `` We're very confident people are going to like what they see on our air _ we're not doing things half-cocked,'' <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. `` They're going to see a very shiny farm network that they're going to want to watch.'' The fledgling Omaha-based network has a 21-member news staff, with bureaus in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. The staff will produce seven hours of live news, weather and markets coverage every week day, and several half-hour summaries daily. `` Currently, agricultural programming is scattered throughout the television system,'' <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. `` There is hit-and-miss coverage on local stations and some largely irrelevant feature material on the major networks.'' Advertisers and home satellite dish dealers are excited about the network. `` There is a definite ` What do we have to lose?' attitude among major advertisers,'' <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. `` Because of satellite communications, our ad rates are lower than a local TV station.'' Agricultural advertisers also have been supportive because `` there's a need for a rifle shot approach to the farmer instead of the shotgun approach,'' he said. Because RFD-TV is a free, unscrambled service, the network could spur lagging satellite dish sales, <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> said. `` We're the first free and clear channel on satellite in the last two years. We're good news for the home satellite dealer. We are definitely a reason for someone to buy home dish,'' he said. Despite high start-up costs of more than $ 3 million, <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON> predicted the channel will turn a profit in its first year. `` We have built-in shows with built-in audiences with built-in advertisers,'' said <PERSON> Gottsch </PERSON>, who is among the network's investors. `` We only have to sell 13 percent of our available ad time to turn a profit.''
</TEXT>
