<FIRST>r f PM-MinutesWar     08-08 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minutes War,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tree Farmer Chronicles Town Meeting Minutes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANCOCK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From his farm in the <LOCATION> Berkshire </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> wages war on small-town autocrats, wresting from them the minutes of meetings that even he admits can make pretty boring reading in his Bulletin. So boring, in fact, that <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> recently cut back publication of his newsletter from twice monthly to once a month. `` I got an inkling that too much was too much,'' he said. But the tree farmer has vowed to keep publishing the recorded gatherings of selectmen, assessors, school and health boards for his 250 readers as long as the money holds out. `` We've been operating in the red and I guess we will always be,'' he said. The not-for-profit newsletter celebrates its first anniversary next month. It has grown to six editions, one for each of the six towns that hand over their minutes, and contains as many minutes as <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> can get. They include such mundane revelations as this, from the May 5 meeting of the <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> board of selectmen: `` Mr. <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON> appeared before the board with 104 lbs. of rocks, stating that they had been picked up on 1,000 ft. of road frontage on his property.'' And this, from the May 8 meeting of the <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> health board: `` <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> came to request rent for the landfill. She says she was not paid for 1987. We will check.'' About 100 copies are sent free to libraries, post offices and other town offices, but <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> has managed to talk the rest of the subscribers into donations ranging from $ 5 to $ 100. Without such gifts, he said, the paper would not survive. He applies the same persuasive logic to advertisers. Recalling a restaurant that recently pulled a $ 50 ad the size of a business card, <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said: `` I could n't convince them that this is a civic thing. No one is going to come to their restaurant to eat because of that ad. It costs $ 100 to eat there anyway.'' <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said he founded the newsletter to keep busy in his retirement. He is a former purchasing agent for an electric company who now runs a Christmas tree farm with his wife, <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON>, 72, who heads the board of selectmen in their town. `` I'm 71 and at my age, if you do n't take up something new, your mind begins to fall into pieces,'' he said. The newsletter proudly lists among its supporters two newspapers, a retired publisher and Pulitzer Prize-winning historian <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> MacGregor </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, who called <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> `` a local friend doing what I think are good things.'' But some apparently disagree. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said officials in a few towns balked at releasing their minutes and complied only after the state attorney general's office told them they were obligated to make the minutes public In at least one case, <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said, his request prompted town officials to take minutes of their meetings for the first time. He said he is still trying to get minutes from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ashford </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> but is loathe to ask the state for help again. `` I'm afraid to stir them up,'' he said of the town officials. `` Then they'll never give them to me.'' The head of the board of selectmen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ashford </LOCATION>, one of the state's smallest towns, with a population of 150 people, said he has refused to mail the minutes to <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>'s home because of the expense. `` The records are there. All he's got to do is come and get them,'' said head selectman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marguerite </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawson </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> board, said she has n't sent minutes to <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> because she has no time to edit them for publication by the time they are typed up, usually several weeks after the meeting `` If he wants, he can sit down at our meetings and take notes,'' she said. `` But I do n't have time to play around with his newsletter. ... It's a sticky situation. I'm not trying to keep anything from him, but I'm a busy woman. I work days and do this -LRB- board business -RRB- at night.'' <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said he's lost $ 2,500 so far on the newsletter, but he plans to get it up to 20 editions before calling it quits. `` If I can do it here, by <PERSON> George </PERSON>, I can do it anywhere,'' he said.
</TEXT>
