<HEAD>London Shares Higher; Fall From Peaks On Interest Rate Hike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices were higher early Monday afternoon, but below their best levels as market makers responded to a hike in British interest rates with widespread markdowns. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 2.6 points, or 0.1 percent, at 1,878.5, at about 12:30 p.m., after reaching as much as 9.3 points higher in early trading. The index was up 8.5 points moments before the rate hike flashed across traders' computer screens. Prices rose to their best levels in early business on the back of an early round of buying by institutional investors. Also boosting shares was widespread positive sentiment, reinforced by favorable weekend press comment about <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> equities. But the signal by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> at about midday for a rise in the commercial banks' base lending rate to 11 percent from 10.5 percent pulled shares sharply lower. The rate move, which took the market by surprise, sparked a bit of selling, but markdowns took the biggest toll on shares, a dealer said. Trading activity, after the early morning spurt in buying, tapered off sharply by late morning. Activity was concentrated in a few, selected shares that were the subject of market speculation or brokerage recommendations. Stock exchange volume by midday was a modest 189.3 million shares compared with 252.5 million shares at the same time Friday.
