<FIRST>d f PM-RegenerativeAgriculture     08-08 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Regenerative Agriculture,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer Aims To Reduce Production Costs, Protect Soil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENUP, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>'s rather unconventional approach to farming began with a simple observation _ one crop can help another crop grow. `` When we plowed down a crop of alfalfa, we had the best corn ever,'' said <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>. `` I had been taught to use all these chemicals. That really gets you to thinking.'' So, <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON> decided five years ago to abandon chemically intensive agriculture and experiment with plants like hairy vetch and rye. They control weeds, add nutrients and organic matter to the soil, and protect the land from erosion _ the natural way, he said. `` The yields have not suffered, in fact they might have picked up a hair,'' said <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>, who now raises corn and soybeans with fewer commercial fertilizers and pesticides. `` That's money in your pocket.'' <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>, 33, recently showed other interested farmers some of the techniques _ successful and unsuccessful _ that he uses on his 400-acre farm in <LOCATION> Cumberland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. It is one of 14 farms across the nation cooperating in experiments sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Rodale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Emmanus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, a nonprofit group doing research on regenerative agriculture. `` We need to diversify crops and methods, stop soil erosion and rely less on fossil fuels,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Rodale </ORGANIZATION>'s midwest research coordinator. `` The systems we develop here will be around for our children and our grandchildren.'' During a wagon tour of his farm, <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON> offered some pointers: _ Fall-planted hairy vetch can be turned under the soil in the spring to supply nitrogen for corn, eliminating the need for that fertilizer in commercial form `` These cover crops do n't let weeds get started in the spring,'' said <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>. `` That vetch will even smother out horseweed.'' _ A field of tall, lush corn was cultivated to kill weeds and grasses before they got a good start Herbicides are a last resort. `` You've got to have a rotary hoe or you might as well throw up your hands and go to town,'' said <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>, who paid $ 15 for a small used one at a sale. `` If that does n't work, you can always come back and spray later.'' _ A field of dead vetch and little corn demonstrated the problem of planting the grain into the vetch without plowing during a dry year The vetch sucked all the moisture out and the corn did n't germinate <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON> also experiments with spring peas as a cover crop to provide nitrogen for corn. He raises melons and other produce in small irrigated fields to sell locally. He produces his own seed for vetch, rye and soybeans, buying only commercial hybrid corn seed. And, he adds fertilizers only when a soil test indicates it will be cost effective. `` We just keep trying things,'' said <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON>. `` The more I do this, the more enthused I get.'' <PERSON> Holsapple </PERSON> said the trial-and-error and the work involved in this kind of farming operation are worthwhile, from a social and economic standpoint. `` There's more profit _ no doubt about it.''
</TEXT>
