<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many hospital administrators list new technology as a major cause of escalating health-care costs, according to a new poll. The poll appears in the Monday issue of <ORGANIZATION> HealthWeek </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. It was released in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> Sunday, the day before the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> was to open its three-day convention here. According to the poll, 32 percent of hospital administrators see technology as the most important contributor to rising health-care costs. In addition to blaming technology for boosting costs, the administrators cited labor costs and salaries -LRB- 20 percent -RRB-, government regulations -LRB- 10 percent -RRB-, personnel shortages, and lack of reimbursement as other leading causes the study reprots. The SRI Gallup poll, conducted by phone among 100 administrators at 27 rural, 38 urban and 35 suburban hospitals across the country, examines issues affecting the delivery of health care services. The poll, which has an error range of plus or minus 9.8 percent, said that 78 percent of the hospital administrators believe the federal government's cost-containment errors are hurting the quality of hospital patient care. Seven in 10 of the respondents said their hospitals make a profit on overall patient revenues, one-third said they did not. Asked if their hospitals make a profit on Medicare patients, 64 percent said they did not. Although 51 percent of the administrators said there has been no substantial change in the difficulty of getting malpractice insurance in the past five years, and 11 percent feel it is easier to get now, 33 percent said it is more difficult to obtain malpractice insurance today. Utilization review, a highly publicized cost-containment practice, has improved the quality of care for 50 percent of the hospitals, but 32 percent of the administrators said the practice had no effect and 17 percent said it had actually hurt the quality of care. Nearly one in four administrators, the largest percentage of respondents to the question, believes the number of AIDS patients will increase by 26 percent or more in the next five years. Four in five believe it is unacceptable for a medical professional to refuse to treat an AIDS patient, the study indicates. Commenting on the nursing shortage, seven in 10 administrators believe it presents a moderate to serious problem. Most administrators, 78 percent, are convinced that substantial pay boosts would have no impact on the nursing shortage according to the poll. <ORGANIZATION> HealthWeek </ORGANIZATION> is a newspaper serving the health industry. SRI Gallup, based in <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, is a health-care marketing research firm and is a sister group to the Gallup Organization.
</TEXT>
