<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 South Korean companies paid $ 321 million in royalties for high-technology imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries during the first half of the year, government figures show. Statistics published Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> showed that the royalty payment for the first half was up from $ 226 million in the same period in 1987. Officials attributed the sharp increase to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s growing demand for high technology for electric, electronic and chemical products and machinery. Royalties for electric and electronic technology more than doubled, to $ 134 million from $ 66 million a year earlier, according to the statistics. Royalty payments for machinery during the six-month period rose 19.6 percent, to $ 61 million. Royalties for oil refining and chemicals doubled, to $ 54 million. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was the largest supplier of technology to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> during the period with $ 161 million, followed by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with $ 112 million, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with $ 10 million and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> with $ 8 million.
