<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices were little changed today in quiet dealings as traders geared up for the government's quarterly refunding. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year issue, which fell -RCB- point or $ 7.50 per $ 1,000 in face amount on Friday, was off 1-32 point at midday. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price, held at 9.12 percent, unchanged from late Friday. Analysts said they expect traders to snap up the $ 11 billion in three-year notes the government is scheduled to sell on Tuesday. Another $ 11 billion in 10-year issues will be sold the following day. `` While the economy is clearly stronger than people anticipated, and that should knock the bond market down, good buying interest in the refunding is supporting'' the credit markets, said <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Held </ORGANIZATION>, chief financial economist at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. Bondholders worry that a strong economy will bring about higher inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income securities and causes interest rates to rise. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term governments fell 3-32 point to 1-16 point, intermediate maturities were 1-32 point to 1-16 point lower, and long-term issues were off 5-32 point, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. Corporate bonds were slightly higher. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.15 to 283.86. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills slipped to 7.08 percent as the discount rate fell 1 basis point to 6.88 percent. Yields on six-month bills rose to 7.61 as the discount rose 2 basis points to 7.25. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.03 percent as the discount rose 2 basis points to 7.48 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, which is paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 7 -RCB- percent, up from 7 11-16 percent late Friday.
