<HEAD>Dollar Gains Except Against Pound, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar closed higher against all the major currencies except the British pound in European trading Monday. Gold prices were mixed. The pound rose after British commercial banks raised their base lending rate by half a percentage point to 11 percent, the second increase in less than a month. Traders said the dollar gained after the news late last Friday of a higher-than-expected rise in the number of Americans at work. That would pump more money into the American economy and started speculation that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates will be raised soon to control inflation. The West German central bank and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> made concerted sales of dollars Monday to stem the dollar's rise and pulled the dollar back from its highest levels of the day, dealers said. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.7022 late Monday, more expensive for buyers than Friday's late $ 1.6977. Other late rates Monday, compared with Friday's late rates, included: 1.9000 West German marks, up from 1.8890; 1.5857 Swiss francs, up from 1.5757; 6.3950 French francs, up from 6.3675; 2.1435 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1315; 1,399.50 Italian lire, up from 1,393.00; 1.2097 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2050. Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> the dollar exchanged at 133.97 Japanese yen at the close, up from 133.12 yen. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> later the dollar traded at 133.60 yen. Gold bullion prices were higher in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major market, and lower in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>. Swiss traders said trading was dull and low in volume. Gold closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 432.25 a troy ounce, up from $ 432.10 late Friday, and in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> at $ 432 bid, down from $ 433. Gold in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> closed at $ 434 bid, up from Saturday's $ 433.99. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 6.78 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.89.
