<SECOND>BC-American Brands-Suit,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bondholders File Suit Against American Brands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of 19 institutional investors filed suit Monday charging that <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> violated securities laws by misstating facts when it offered to buy $ 1.5 billion in debt as part of its acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The complaint, filed against both companies in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, seeks $ 350 million in damages. Holders of <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term debt passed up an opportunity to sell out in late February. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> offered to buy two issues of debt at 103 percent and 104 percent of face value plus accrued interest, but the offer expired without the company receiving anywhere near the 51 percent response needed to trigger the purchases. The bonds currently are trading below the price offered by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>. The bondholders, led by <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Forstmann-Leff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, claim they based their decision not to sell on <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>' assertion that it would retain <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION> as a wholly owned subsidiary. The plaintiffs, who hold about $ 600 million of <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.5 billion in outstanding debt, had expected <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> to sell only a `` few segments of <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION>'s businesses that did not fit into the core business strategy.'' Four months later, however, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> announced it would sell most of <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION> _ including its debt _ to <ORGANIZATION> Riklis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> paid <PERSON> Riklis </PERSON> to retain five E-II businesses <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION>'s outstanding debt is now the obligation of <PERSON> Riklis </PERSON>. In their lawsuit, the bondholders allege <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> `` pursued a secret strategy completely inconsistent with the statements made in the tender offer document'' when it was acquiring <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION> shares in February for $ 17.05 a share, or about $ 2.7 billion including debt. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Conforti </PERSON> said the company had been advised that `` the suits are without merit.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> `` made it clear at the outset that we would not assume the indebtedness.'' American Brands disclaimed any legal responsibility for the bonds before the merger with <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION> was completed, saying the debt would remain <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION>'s responsibility once it became a subsidiary. The suit seeks compensatory and punitive damages. The two bond issues in question come due in March 1997 and March 1999. Interest payments on the debt total about $ 194 million, according to published estimates.
