<HEAD>Labor Department Unveils Proposal To Help Migrant Workers Hurt by
Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Relief Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Labor Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> announced a $ 14.8 million plan Monday to meet the emergency survival needs of thousands of migrant and seasonal farm workers left without money or jobs because of the drought. But Rep. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s package is not enough to help migrant workers stranded across the drought-parched <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> without a job or enough money to finance the return trip home `` When you're looking at the amount of money big farmers, agri-conglomerates are getting, they really are not providing for the bottom-rung people who do the harvesting and stoop labor,'' <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> said. `` They should have been more fair in trying to bring relief to these people,'' said <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON>, himself a former migrant worker. <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> said he had sought $ 20 million to $ 25 million, which would have come closer to `` meeting short-term survival needs.'' A $ 3.9 billion package of drought assistance for farmers, ranchers and dairy producers passed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday and could receive final legislative approval as early as Tuesday in the House. <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> said he was working with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> to free up more money for the migrant workers Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> promised the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would marshal funds quickly. She said she also was writing to state governors and agencies to recommend `` special employment services and unemployment insurance consideration for migrant farm workers.'' `` The severe drought in some parts of the nation has had a devastating effect on migrant farm workers and their families,'' Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said in a statement. `` Some are stranded without work or money to return home, while others face extreme hardship at their home base.'' Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said she has authorized existing migrant worker programs operating under <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> grants to use up to 15 percent of their current funding for emergency services such as health care, transportation and temporary shelter. The agency said that could mean up to $ 9.5 million may be spent. She said another $ 5 million has been set aside from a Job Partnership Training Act reserve account for displaced workers to be used specifically for migrant farm workers hurt by the drought. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also said portions of some states may be declared disaster areas, triggering a disaster unemployment insurance program. Twenty-two states have asked the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> to be designated drought-disaster areas. These states have an estimated 200,000 migrant and seasonal farm workers, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. They are <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCAT