to North Dakota sted Montana. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Conoco, a
subsidiary ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will sell its oil and gas holdings in the <LOCATION> Williston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Conoco </ORGANIZATION> for an undisclosed sum, company officials announced Monday. The sale is part of <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>' strategy to divest non-strategic assets, company spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said. `` It did not have a good fit for us,'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said of <LOCATION> Williston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>. Since 1985, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> has sold gas plants at <LOCATION> Williston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tioga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Conoco </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, will obtain <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>' interest in about 175 oil and gas wells that produce about 4,000 barrels of oil and 2.8 million cubic feet of natural gas a day Also included in the sale are 234,000 undeveloped acres in eastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>' interest in the <LOCATION> Williston </LOCATION> property amounted to about 2,000 barrels of oil and 1 million cubic feet of gas a day. He said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production last year was 113,000 barrels of oil and 772 million cubic feet of natural gas a day. Industry analysts say the amount of domestic oil and gas reserves up for sale has about doubled in the past year because of the market created by high exploration costs. The transactions usually reflect the seller's need to reduce debt and the buyer's desire for proven production at a cost lower than that of exploring for new reserves, the analysts said.
