<HEAD>Meese Approves Joint Agreement for Detroit News, Free Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> will be allowed to merge their business and production operations because the smaller <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> was in danger of financial failure stemming from years of steady and apparently irreversible losses, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said Monday. In approving the application for a joint operating agreement, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> rejected the recommendation of a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> administrative law judge who said the two newspapers' pricing policies were unrealistic. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, however, said there was little prospect for the Free Press to return to profitability in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s highly competitive market. `` For me, the continuing and persistent operating losses suffered by the Free Press over the course of nearly a decade, with no prospect of unilaterally reversing that economic condition in the foreseeable future, describes a newspaper ` in danger of financial failure','' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said in his opinion. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> told reporters that the Free Press' losses were not manipulated but came `` from intense competition.'' The <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> joint operating agreement was the fifth approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> under the Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970, which allows limited antitrust exemption to preserve independent editorial voices in a community where one newspaper is in danger of failing. Previous partial mergers were approved for newspapers in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, in 1974, <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> in 1979, <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, in 1980 and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in 1982. The Free Press, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and the News, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had asked permission in May 1986 to merge their advertising, circulation and production operations under a law designed to preserve newspaper competition The newspapers, which rank among the nation's 10 largest, said the Free Press was in danger of going out of business without the joint operating agreement. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s directors had voted to shut down the Free Press if the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had rejected the application for a joint operating agreement. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> said in January that the Free Press' operating losses had totaled $ 100 million since 1979, and that the News had lost about $ 75 million in the same period. The Free Press lost $ 18 million on revenues of $ 172 million in 1987. `` This decision reaffirms the will of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that two independent editorial voices should be preserved wherever possible in the cities of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Alvah </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> chairman, said in a statement issued in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Free Press Publisher <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said: `` This is the best single day of my years at the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. It leads the way to the next century of service for the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, which already has been part of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> for more than a century and a half.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON> and president <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curley </PERSON> also expressed gratification. `` We said all along that the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> was the only way to preserve two independent news and editorial voices,'' they said in a statement issued from <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in suburban <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` The attorney general's decision is in the best interest of the community, the readers, the advertisers and the employees.'' Said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedheim </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>: `` While the administrative law judge in the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> case misapplied the statute in some important ways, we are pleased that the attorney general appears to have taken a view more consistent with the intent of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> administrative law judge, <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Needelman </PERSON>, recommended in December 1987 that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> deny the request on grounds that the newspapers' losses were due to unrealistic circulation and advertising discounts aimed at forcing each other out of business. The newspapers denied <PERSON> Needelman </PERSON>'s assertion, saying he lacked an understanding of the newspaper business. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>, publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, one of several suburban <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> papers that had criticized the joint operating agreement request, said he was `` quite surprised'' that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had ignore the advice of the judge who had heard all the evidence in the case `` and made a very studious decision.'' While <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was still considering the case, Free Press Editor <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> rejected three cartoons about <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> by staff cartoonist <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>. Another Knight-Ridder paper, the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, also decided not to publish editorial cartoons about <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> while the case was pending. Newspaper employee unions and <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> initially opposed the partial merger, but most dropped their opposition after <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> directors voted to shut down the Free Press if they failed to win approval of a joint operating agreement. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said the owner's threat to close the Free Press was noted in the record of the case, but was not the deciding factor in his decision. The <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION>, the last employee union to oppose the joint operating agreement, dropped its opposition July 25. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> and most of the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> congressional delegation supported the agreement. The Free Press had circulation in March of 647,763 daily and 721,676 on Sundays, the 10th largest circulation in the nation, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circulation </ORGANIZATION>. The circulation of the News was 688,211 daily and 836,331 on Sundays, the eighth largest nationally, the bureau said. The Free Press was founded in 1831 and purchased by a predecessor of <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> in 1940. The News was founded in 1873 and purchased by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> in 1986.
