<HEAD>Texas Air's Loss Widens Sharply; TWA's Profit Nearly Doubles</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with Texas Air results; changes
dateline and summary line; ADDS more reasons for TWA gains; No
pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's biggest airline company, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, reported Monday that its second-quarter net loss widened sharply, while <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its profit after taxes nearly doubled. Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> said its net loss widened to $ 255.9 million from a loss of $ 27 million in the second quarter of 1987. The company blamed a significant part of the loss on government investigations of alleged safety problems at its two main subsidiaries, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s second-quarter revenue slipped 1.4 percent, to $ 2.13 billion from $ 2.16 billion a year earlier. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> launched investigations of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> in mid-April that were unprecedented in their scope. The probes, which continued for most of the second quarter, concluded that both airlines were being run safely. However, a federal report concluded that labor turmoil at Miami-based Eastern must be defused before it creates risks to passengers. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> said Monday the investigations cost <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> a total of more than $ 60 million in lost revenue and $ 14 million in expenses such as overtime, advertising and legal and accounting fees. `` Both airlines have implemented various marketing and service programs to counter the effects of these investigations on consumer confidence, but the companies have continued to experience some revenue losses beyond the second quarter due to them,'' <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> said in a press statement. At <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, the second-quarter net loss was $ 89.8 million, compared with net income of $ 27.1 million a year earlier. Eastern's revenue in the most recent quarter declined to $ 1 billion from $ 1.2 billion <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> posted a $ 19.9 million loss before a $ 131 million adjustment associated with a re-estimation of its air traffic liability. The adjustment had been announced earlier and had no impact on <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s cash position, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> said. Including the adjustment, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 150.9 million on revenue of $ 1.1 billion in the second quarter. In the same period a year earlier, the airline lost $ 71.1 million on revenue of $ 1 billion. The results in the latest quarter brought <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s net loss for the first half of the year to $ 380.1 million, widened from a loss of $ 127.7 million in the first six months of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s first-half revenue rose 1.4 percent, to $ 4.26 billion from $ 4.20 billion. New York-based <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> said its net profit almost doubled in the second quarter from a year earlier, largely due to a cash payment it received from a lawsuit against its former owner, the late <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>. The nation's seventh-largest airline said its net income jumped to $ 97.2 million, or $ 2.70 a share, from $ 52.8 million, or $ 1.28 a share, in the second quarter of 1987. In addition to a $ 49.9 million gain from the Hughes lawsuit, <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings also benefitted in the quarter from cost controls, a rebound in international passenger traffic which had been hurt by fears of terrorism, and the long-term advantages of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s merger with <ORGANIZATION> Ozark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s second-quarter revenue rose 8.6 percent, to $ 1.14 billion from $ 1.05 billion a year earlier. Profit in the latest quarter includes the $ 49.9 million gain from a cash judgment awarded to <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 in its long-standing lawsuit against <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> management's suit, originally filed in 1962, alleged that the eccentric multimillionaire failed to provide the carrier with adequate aircraft. Although a <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court decided in <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s favor last year, the payment was not made until the second quarter. In the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 44.7 million, or 50 cents a share, compared with a net loss of $ 2 million in the first six months of 1987. First-half revenue increased 9.6 percent, to $ 2.06 billion from $ 1.88 billion.
