<HEAD>Hershey Foods Selling Friendly Ice Cream</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERSHEY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, deciding to jettison its nine-year venture into the restaurant industry, said Monday it is selling its <ORGANIZATION> Friendly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restaurant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 375 million. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said the company felt it could better use its resources concentrating on its primary business _ consumer food products. `` Although Friendly has been a significant part of <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, our decision to sell Friendly is based upon our continuing review of our strategic plan and evaluation of our business portfolio,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> said in a statement. <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said declining income and other difficult conditions in the restaurant industry figured in <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. Income from the restaurant chain fell to $ 45.6 million in 1986 from $ 50.4 million in 1986. In its 1986 annual report, <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> noted heightened competition, lack of real sales growth, a decrease in customers and difficulty finding workers. Two-thirds of the company's sales gain in the restaurant division from 1985 to 1986 came from new and acquired restaurants rather than from higher volume at existing restaurants. Besides its chocolate and confectionery products, <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> also produces several brands of pasta, including <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Giorgio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> and American Beauty. Friendly, based in <LOCATION> Wilbraham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, owns and operates a chain of about 850 restaurants, which feature moderately priced menu items and ice cream specialities. Friendly's 1987 sales were $ 572 million. <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> said the transaction, which will give it an after-tax gain, should be completed within three months, subject to government approval. <ORGANIZATION> TRC </ORGANIZATION>, a private restaurant holding company based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, owns about 51 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Perkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restaurants </ORGANIZATION>, a publicly traded limited partnership, and 100 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Perkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc.. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> owns and franchices more than 330 restaurants, primarily in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and `` We are pleased to enter phase two of <ORGANIZATION> TRC </ORGANIZATION>'s development with a company boasting the high-quality reputation of Friendly,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> TRC </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive officer. He said Friendly has strong name recognition andd excellent market penetration in the Northeast. Friendly will provide a solid foundation for future growth, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> and Friendly will be operated as separate companies, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON>'s move comes shortly after it announced plans to purchase the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> confectionery operations of <ORGANIZATION> Cadbury-Schweppess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> for $ 270 million plus the assumption of $ 30 million in debt. The purchase, still in progress, will give <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> a wide array of candy lines, stretching from its own well-known products, including Reeses peanut butter candies, to <ORGANIZATION> Cadbury </ORGANIZATION>'s Peter-Paul and York products and <PERSON> Luden </PERSON>'s 5th Avenue bar and cough drops. `` What we're finding is our area of strength is manufacturing, with a primary focus on snacks and confectionery products,'' <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said. `` We do think that puts us in a leadership position of the total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> confectionery market,'' he added.
