<HEAD>Interco Rejects $70 A Share Offer From City Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday rejected as inadequate a sweetened $ 2.68 billion buyout offer from a Washington-based investor group, and took moves to strengthen its defenses against an unwanted takeover. The manufacturer and retailer of apparel and furniture stated that in addition to rejecting the $ 70 a share merger proposal offered earlier Monday by <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, its board of directors approved a plan to sell the company's apparel division, which accounts for nearly a fourth of its sales. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> board concluded that the interests of the company's shareholders were better served by the company's continued pursuit of the restructuring of the company, which is presently under consideration,'' the company said <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> stock, which rose by more than $ 13 a share when the group's initial offer of $ 64 a share was announced July 28, rose $ 4.12 -LCB- to $ 72.50 a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> board also amended its `` poison pill'' defense against hostile takeover, so that it takes effect if a suitor acquires 15 percent or more of <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION>'s 38.4 million outstanding common shares. The company said the change was aimed at preventing an open-market stock accumulation program following the announcement of a proposal to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> or a `` street sweep'' that could accompany or follow a tender offer for the company, in which all <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would not participate equally and at a fair price. <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> owns 8.7 percent, or 3.14 million, of <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION>'s outstanding common shares When it made its initial $ 64 a share offer, valued at about $ 2.46 billion, <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> said it might increase its bid based on further review of information about <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION>. The company had sales of $ 3.34 billion last year, with the apparel group contributing about 24 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> manufactures men's and women's apparel, footwear, furniture and home furnishings. Some of its brand names are among the best known in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Fog clothing, <ORGANIZATION> Florsheim </ORGANIZATION> and Converse shoes, and <PERSON> Broyhill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ethan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> furniture. In addition to its manufacturing operations, <ORGANIZATION> Interco </ORGANIZATION> operates 201 retail locations in 15 states, including home-improvement centers, general merchandise discount stores, mens' specialty apparel shops and specialty department stores.
