<HEAD>Free Press Employees Celebrate Approval Of Partial Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT6 and DT7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspaper employees and executives by turns praised and criticized Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s approval Monday of a partial merger of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> with the Detroit News. Champagne flowed in the newsroom at the Free Press, where the decision brought relief after months of uncertainty over whether <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> would approve the joint operating agreement between the newspaper, the nation's 10th-largest, and the rival News. `` It was like a rush. Waiting for the decision is like living on death row,'' said senior managing editor <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Shine </PERSON>, who had been assigned to write the newspaper's obituary if the joint operating agreement with the News was denied. But critics labeled the deal a blow to competition in the newspaper business. `` This is a travesty of the Newspaper Preservation Act,'' said <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Mleczko </PERSON>, a News reporter who is president of <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 22. `` The two largest media companies in the world can take two newspapers that are in a dead heat and get a monopoly.'' <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> had said it would close the 157-year-old Free Press if the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> with the News, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was denied In <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, top <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> executives praised <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> employees for persevering under difficult conditions and praised <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> for approving the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is good news for the loyal readers and advertisers of the Free Press, for our hard-working and dedicated employees in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and for our shareholders who have shared the burden of enormous operating losses in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> since 1979,'' <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Alvah </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON> and president <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curley </PERSON> also praised the decision. `` We said all along that the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> was the only way to preserve two independent news and editorial voices,'' they said in a statement issued from <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` The attorney general's decision is in the best interest of the community, the readers, the advertisers and the employees.'' Newspaper Guild Local 22, the last of the newspapers' unions to drop its opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>, nevertheless was critical of the decision. The Guild, which has 1,100 members in the two newsrooms, held out for better economic terms before agreeing to withdraw its opposition. `` The losers in this are going to be the readers and advertisers in southeastern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and it could set a precedent where you'll see the elimination of competitive journalism in cities throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Mleczko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapids </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the state's third-largest paper, said he was pleased as a journalist that the merger was approved `` The loss of any daily newspaper would be considered a bad day in journalism by even those of us who think of the Free Press as serious competition,'' said <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>, publisher of the <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> -RRB- Press, said he was surprised <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> would disregard the recommendation of the administrative law judge who presided over hearings on the proposed <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>. `` Judge -LRB- <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Needelman </PERSON> sat and listened to these things and made a very studious decision on it, and it's hard to believe the attorney general would so easily overturn what his own administrative law judge recommended,'' <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON> said. Reactions from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> politicians also varied. State Senator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, who unsuccessfully sought a new law blocking the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>, said `` What has really happened is the annihilation of the Free Press. It will be ` Gannettized' and the quality staff will be reduced because there will be no incentive without any real competition.'' But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, a longtime <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> critic, complemented the attorney general. `` Today's announcement shows what a united community can do and what a united <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> congressional delegation can do. Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s response to that united community is very gratifying indeed,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said.
