<HEAD>U.S. Judge Rules Island Nation Owes $44 Million To Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge ruled Monday that the tiny <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island Republic of <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> must pay an international consortium of banks more than $ 44 million on defaulted loans. The republic, a 200-island archipelago in the south central <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> about 600 miles east of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, borrowed more than $ 30 million to build an electric power generating station in the early 1980s. The nation, once a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trust territory, in March defaulted on the loans and the consortium that had guaranteed the loans had to pay them off. The banks sued the country _ population 14,200 _ for repayment. Under the decision, the banks _ <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grenfell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scotland </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> _ are entitled to collect some $ 44.3 million in unpaid loans, capitalized interest, insurance premiums, fees and expenses In his 57-page opinion, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> said the case presented `` an involved factual matrix and complicated issues of sovereignty and commercial law arising out of the struggle of the unsophisticated island people of <LOCATION> Palau </LOCATION> to achieve independence, both economic and political.'' But the judge concluded the banks were entitled to collect the amounts they had guaranteed. Sweet's ruling was the latest round in a three-year legal battle between the banks, some of the largest in the world, and <PERSON> Palau </PERSON>, whose main industry is fishing. `` This decision is but one step along what may turn out to be a long road, but at least this phase has been completed,'' said Sweet. After a week-long trial in April and final arguments in June, Sweet ruled that <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> willingly waived its right to sovereign immunity, and thus protection from lawsuits, when it signed the loan agreements. Sweet also ruled that <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> failed to prove its contention that the banks had misrepresented how the power plant would pay for itself or that <LOCATION> Palauan </LOCATION> officials signed documents they did not understand.
