<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Lower In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Nikkei morning closing,
details, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar edged higher against the Japanese yen in morning trading Tuesday, while stock prices eased. After opening at 133.62 yen, down from Monday's close of 133.97 yen, the dollar traded in a narrow range and by late morning was changing hands at 133.70 yen. Traders said most currency market participants were monitoring the dollar's movements against the West German mark. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> intervened in the market sporadically to keep the dollar from rising too sharply against the mark in overseas markets The dollar reached 1.90 marks during Monday trading, a level not seen since January 1987. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, down 109.06 points on Monday, fell another 37.81 points to finish the morning session at 28,215.31. Dealers on the stock exchange said the market remained relatively quiet as participants relaxed because of the summer holidays.
